{"share":"0","time":"2013-05-03 13:40:32:000","text":"<p>屯点东西<\/p><p>Abstract：Generalized, persistent, and free-floating anxiety was first described by Freud [<img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/imgpro\/icons\/statusface\/guibai.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"膜拜\"><img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/imgpro\/icons\/statusface\/guibai.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"膜拜\"><img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/imgpro\/icons\/statusface\/guibai.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"膜拜\">] in 1894, although the diagnostic term generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) was not included in classification systems until 1980 in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders-III (DSM-III) [@吴天悦(329147299) 那本神书]. Initially considered a residual category to be used when no other diagnosis could be made[歪打正着么], it is now widely accepted that GAD represents a distinct diagnostic category. <\/p><p>        <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">What is generalized anxiety disorder? Rickels, Karl; Rynn, Moira A.<em>Journal of Clinical Psychiatry<\/em>, Vol 62(Suppl11), 2001, 4-12.<\/span><\/p>","title":"Free-floating Anxiety","view":"21","textlength":"1047","comment":"0","access":"0","type":"0"}
