{"share":"0","time":"2013-02-09 00:45:05:000","text":"<p>    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">因为偶然溜进耳朵的几串音符，去看了《花样年华》的电影。往常总是看过一部电影，后来细节场景统统记不清，却仍回荡着那几段调子着了魔般回甘。《如果爱》这样，《云图》亦如此。这次倒着来了回，竟超过了期待。<\/span><\/p><p>不算影迷，看的电影还没小时候的动画多。要不是因为大幅海报的硬机械或是细腻色彩的唆使，我大抵极少愿意呆在黑漆漆的电影院里消磨这两三个小时。虽然电影未必难看，但除非好奇心过重，不然要交出时间的支配权着实不那么容易说服。小清新、恋爱的电影看得极少，大概是海报的雷同、色调的相近提不起胃口，瞥见地铁站《全城高考》占据的极佳位置不禁语塞，和《那些年》几乎一致的色调注定了故事的格局和走向；史诗类的电影同样看得极少，重述历史总有点翻旧账的困苦，林林总总地算起人这可悲的动物究竟犯了多少罪孽。生活已经饱含着众人的悲喜剧，何必特意去戏里找？<\/p><p>以前也会看豆瓣读书和电影的评分，后来发现大概是和普罗大众口味不合，平均分以有限样本代表总体的意义在我身上屡屡失效。反正也在3个标准差之外了，犯不着牵强附合。后来发现，也不尽然。就像确定了硬币正反面的选项，追随那翻滚的银色抛起，减速到零，加速下落，时间坍缩。合掌的瞬间，答案已经推门进了屋，谁管那硬币是正是反。看过觉得赞的电影，我哪里会强迫症一样特意去豆瓣查下评分打个5星？<\/p><p>少年pi是第一部让我觉得没有被广大豆友开除豆籍的作品。曾在少年间广为流传的《海上钢琴师》、《辛德勒的名单》、《千与千寻》都未曾让我有什么惊天动地的感动或者领悟，当然pi也没有，但至少有了些细丝一样水母的触觉。大抵是我悟性太低，又大概只是因为故事性强的电影不是我的菜，就像我不读小说一样。<\/p><p>《花样年华》的长镜头细腻地极其合我胃口，摄像头在三折镜间摇摆，交替地映出两张脸。不知怎么就想起了蒙娜丽莎的笑，迷迷糊糊总跟着晃荡。街角长镜头张的步子和音乐慢三拍惊人地融到一起，甚至梁走下台阶的节奏都暗暗和着。指尖细微的动作、眼神的游移、古而不旧的小巷背景、粤语和上海话的杂糅。一个几乎不算故事的故事，看得极其安然平静。最后对着树洞讲秘密倒像是个费解的败笔，大概是导演的情结所致。<\/p><p>故事多是这么些，悲喜离恨，或许还有尴尬矛盾纠结恐惧。换位思考总是换不过来的，一场戏过后倒愈发划深了一条铅笔印迹，台上台下两个世界。讲故事和听故事，监视和被监视，一条过道两重心境，鱼永远不用飞睁着眼看就行。<\/p><p>但或许哪天水涸了呢？<\/p><p>噢，抱歉。这故事我们改天再演吧！<\/p>","title":"关于电影","view":"118","textlength":"1123","comment":"4","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"2","time":"2013-01-31 11:59:09:000","text":"<p>    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">前阵子北京的同学到上海，说起新修的地铁能一路连起南锣鼓巷和后海。不知怎么又提及公主坟，方知那是个造了地铁被掘墓的地方。北京的胡同、四合院依然在拆，这些日子pm2.5占据了主场，也不太听得那些遥远的闷响了。大上海和老北京，珍藏的东西毕竟不太可能一样。<\/span><\/p><p>回上海后照例去美术馆晃了圈，原本突兀却张牙舞爪含着抗争气息的支架被拆了。牌子上小小的字，门口的警戒线，不怎么好的天气，人高马大的保安挺着肚子来回晃荡。本不该有什么莫名其妙的感怀，屋子还在，只不过少了个美术馆的名号。纵使最后只剩个餐厅守着这栋老宅，它也不会比现在更糟。思忖半天，只能归结于天气够不上明朗，没有夕阳和分层的天际弥补称呼缺失的遗憾&mdash;&mdash;哎，我总不能直呼它南京西路325号。<\/p><p>称呼的变化大概更能引起共鸣和感慨，就像说好的棉花糖却一直都只是一场笑话。<\/p><p>龙门楼底楼门厅的色调改得有些像饭店大堂，倒是更加凸显三楼白光的无力。习惯习惯大概也就习惯了，就和广播操、眼保健操一样，每套都被吐槽很久仿佛总是越改越不入目一样。老羊总说以前晚上还能数星星，现在上海灯多了就看不见星星了。起初还倍感可惜，后来才知道有个词叫夜上海。<\/p><p>变化、孤立、价值大概都是让人不安的东西，以至于被孤立者不仅承蒙同情还同时背负着声讨。或许是人总习惯用家长式的判断表述预言&mdash;&mdash;噢，也是，立意不清态度不明的文章是要被打入冷宫的&mdash;&mdash;或许是觉得至今无法形成所谓&ldquo;自己的&rdquo;判断有些惶恐，或许是观望良久终于找到插话的机会必须冒个泡声明自己的存在。道理啊，总是说着说着就自我说服，越说越有理的。<\/p><p>网络的神奇在于看似交火激烈、涉及面极广的大战实际上有些开着气囊对撞的意味，结果弹性碰撞，损耗一些口水和网费，各自退回原位。在这样取样极度不均衡的局面下，倒是扩大了当事者对影响力的判断。说来其实挺有趣的。<\/p><p>有阵子时兴声讨学霸，吵老吵去学霸们还是读着自己的砖头书，倒是围观者依依呀呀唱了好久的折子。人家乐意用勺子还非得逼他使筷子，循循善诱逐层上升，最后得出&ldquo;是中国人就得用筷子&rdquo;之类陈述实在有点奇妙。<\/p><p>时常是无力改变什么却又必须做些什么，价值或许仅仅是避免虚无的一类屏障。当语境是全人类的时候，我们并不能做出判断，只是套套范式举举例子，说说什么是XX之类应然的话。当个人的角色被纳入考量，最优解成了理性范围内的东西，时间才有了非历史的意义。<\/p>","title":"景致","view":"146","textlength":"1138","comment":"22","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"0","time":"2013-01-28 22:29:33:000","text":"<p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>似乎该写些什么来总结一下过去的2012年，传说中的末日年过得有点不伦不类。并没有太好的记录习惯，到了大学尤其如此，一学期下来都没怎么写东西。或许该把码日志当作一种习惯，许久不写真心手生。20号回到上海，有了一个月的寒假却又与许多朋友擦肩而过，着实有些可惜。<\/p><p>回了上中，学校还是和以前一样，湿漉漉的空气、灯光有些压抑的高三，知道了不催有新娘、Boss要离开的消息，不禁担心明年艺术节大合唱前的颁奖环节是否会就此消弭&mdash;&mdash;总不能借着这个时候让伸长脖子逆光仰望着童鞋们补上错失的周爽吧&hellip;&hellip;还是走得太匆忙，下回自个儿回去转转。<\/p><p>从红楼出来碰到小柴，于是他又以他一贯的口吻配以长镜头动画表情叫住我：&ldquo;噢，孙卉，你跟我来一下。&rdquo;说实话，我好奇小柴神奇的表达系统已经很久了，包括成语的嵌套、说话时表情和头部姿势的协调以及复杂的脚步变化和以足底为轴心的单摆运动= =&hellip;&hellip;小柴在读在职心理学硕士，让我帮忙找一个量表。但是看到小柴论文的名字，顿时不淡定了啊！《高中生&ldquo;场依存-场独立&rdquo;的认知风格与出生星盘水星状态的研究&mdash;&mdash;对人格与出生时间的关系的再探索》，论文里满满的占星学解释啊！这如何让对占星一窍不通的人看懂= =&hellip;最神奇的是，小柴在上中以240人的样本量做实验发现了数据的显著性啊&hellip;&hellip;果然世界太奇妙，不是我等凡人可以理解的。<\/p><p>在北京的一学期可能还是过得有点仓促，虽然听了些不虚此行的演出，几次聚会还都相当欢乐，但总觉遗憾。错过了秋天，到冬天要出门就需要不小的勇气，可惜没怎么好好发现北京城，开春了出去找个地方躲躲或许是不错的选择。果然在北京这种接地气的地方呆了一阵回上海就不会小文艺了&hellip;&hellip;那天情系母校原来得讲从自招到高考，之前翻了翻高三时的人人状态，果然是满满迁客骚人的气息。的确，也就在那种紧迫而抑制的环境里才会浓缩出一些我至今还能自己嚼嚼的句子。如今，呵呵了，透明的屋子阳光不错但是总难呆久，顾忌太多。<\/p><p>在北京入冬前还会写信，后来就基本是收信。等上海的信寄过来实在太漫长，当然，有时查楼层信箱，不小心翻到写给奶茶的各类信件，看看署名神马的还是能照亮一整个晚上的。老沈的明信片来得太突然，又是一副自由人嘲笑狱中人的赶脚，噢，也可能只是我的投射。<\/p><p>回家顿觉生活安逸：进门开灯、睡觉还能通过床边的另一个开关把灯关掉、厨房有直饮水。老妈开始学钢琴，老爸照样打游戏。<\/p><p>备机的伟大：诺基亚终究是诺基亚。<\/p>","title":"随记 Jan.28th","view":"78","textlength":"1156","comment":"0","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"12","time":"2013-01-27 21:24:43:000","text":"<p align=\"center\">    <span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt;\"><strong>             <br>             <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">Q&amp;A<\/span><\/strong><\/span><\/p><p align=\"center\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">目录<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">1. 催眠是怎么做到的？... 2<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">2. 心理學到底屬於自然科學還是社會科學？... 3<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">3. 心理学为什么算理科？还有涉及医学和社会人性方面的心理学有什么区别？... 4<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">4. 我觉得心理学难以量化是硬伤%&hellip;&hellip;.. 4<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">5. 心理系毕业后有什么就业方向... 4<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">6. 心理学有终极的研究方向之类的么, 比如物理学的终极方向是大统一理论这样的.... 5<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">7. 心理學到底研究普遍心理現象，還是研究個人心理差異的不同表征？... 5<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">8. 学心理的人会成为别人的&ldquo;垃圾桶&rdquo;吗？... 5<\/span><\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p><p align=\"center\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\"><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/span><\/p><p align=\"center\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">孙卉<\/span><\/p><p align=\"center\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">清华大学心理系<\/span><\/p><p align=\"center\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">2013年1月<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\"><strong>             <br>         <\/strong><\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\"><strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/span><\/p><h1>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">1. 催眠是怎么做到的？<\/span><\/h1><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">（1）催眠的一般步骤<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">减少外界干扰，进入舒适状态。随后催眠师要求被试将注意力集中在某些物体上并用平和语言引导或暗示被试体验。诸如&ldquo;放松&rdquo;等。被试进入催眠状态后并没有入睡，其脑电记录和清醒时是一样的。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">（2）并非所有人都能被催眠<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">催眠的实现建立在催眠师和被治疗者之间的信任和契约基础上。而且个体间受暗示的程度存在差异。10%-20%的人极易被催眠，而约10%的人完全无法被催眠。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">（3）催眠的理论：<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">a.社会认知或角色扮演的观点<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">社会心理学家斯帕诺斯（Spanos，1982）提出。他认为，催眠状态下的行为实质上都是在人正常的自主范围之内。因为，所有催眠研究使用的被试都是在受催眠影响的敏感性测量中获得较高分数的人。这些人&ldquo;非常投入，希望自己在催眠实验中成为一个好的被试&rdquo;。他们知道研究者要对清醒状态和催眠状态作比较，被催眠者想证明催眠的确有效。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">在斯帕诺斯的一项研究中，两组学生都要听关于催眠术的讲座。在讲座中，告诉其中一组学生，胳膊僵直的感觉是在催眠过程中不由自主出现的现象，其余内容完全相同。然后对这两组学生进行催眠。结果显示，在讲座中听到有关胳膊僵直的信息的那组学生，在没有给出任何指导语的情况下，就有人&ldquo;不由自主地&rdquo;表现出了这种行为。而在另一组学生中，没有一人胳膊变得僵直。这说明，人是按自己对催眠的想象来行动的。人们之所以在催眠状态下做出某种特定行为，是因为他们觉得催眠就应该是那样，而不是因为催眠改变了他们的意识状态。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">b.意识分理论<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">美国心理学家希尔加德（Ernest R．Hilgard，1904&mdash;2001）认为人的意识有执行和监督两种基本功能：执行功能使我们控制和规范自己的行为；监督功能使我们观察自己的行为。催眠弱化或断开意识对行为的监控。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">在实验（Hilgard，1968）中，催眠师先暗示被试，其左手在催眠后将失去一切痛觉。当他进入催眠状态后，催眠师就将其左手放入冰水中。这时要求他口头回答他的左手是否感到刺痛，他报告说不痛。但如果将他的右手放在按钮上，并对他说如感到左手刺痛就用右手按按钮。结果发现，虽然他在口头上回答说没有刺痛感，但其右手则会按下按钮。这说明，在催眠状态下，口头回答的不痛是在催眠暗示下所产生的意识经验，是扭曲的、失真的。右手按按钮的行为表达出了被催眠者自己的感受，是真实的。因此，催眠将意识分为两部分，一部分对疼痛没有觉知，而另一部分（即隐秘观察者）则能够觉知到。这个实验显示，意识在催眠状态下是分离的。&nbsp;<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">希尔加德认为，分离的意识是一个平常而普通的现象。例如，人们常会将车开出很长一段距离，其间会对交通信号和其他车辆作出反应，但过后想不出自己是怎样作出反应的。在这个例子中，意识明显被分开，一部分用来开车，另一部分用来想其他的事情。这种体验在较早时被称为&ldquo;高速公路催眠&rdquo;。在这种条件下，支配开车的那部分意识甚至也会 &ldquo;记忆缺失&rdquo;，类似于催眠后遗忘。总之，希尔加德的观点表明，催眠是意识的一种可以解释的变化，并在日常经历中可以看到这种变化。&nbsp;<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">[参考：普通心理学，北京师范大学出版社；心理学导论（第2版），人民出版社]<\/span><\/p><h1>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">2. 心理學到底屬於自然科學還是社會科學？&nbsp;&nbsp;<\/span><\/h1><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">这个问题很尴尬&hellip;&hellip;<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">因为说自然科学会让人自然而然联想起物理、化学、数学这类所谓探寻自然界奥秘的学问。人们的发现不论怎样迥异或接近都只是在&ldquo;发现&rdquo;真理，而自然的运行规律并不因为我们而改变。人固然可以坚信太阳不从东边升起，固然可以认为欧式几何是世界的主宰，但不论怎样，结论的推翻或证明，都意味着更接近人们预设的、期待的终点。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">但社会科学又显得不太一样。它借用科学的手段（姑且这么说吧&hellip;&hellip;这里科学的定义不太确切）来研究我们身在其中的现象和行为。倘若自然科学是看别人下棋，社会科学就更有那么点当局者迷的味道。人们怀疑社会科学的结论一部分原因或许在于相信自己、以及与自己想法相似的人可以推翻这一结论。人们惯常认为这个以人构成的世界应该随时受到人的掌控，不管是小写的&ldquo;人&ldquo;还是大写的&rdquo;人&ldquo;。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">心理学的研究领域或许横跨了两边，这并不是件好事，因为它有时落得两边不讨好。自然科学角度的心理学以认知心理学、生理心理学、神经心理学、心理药物学为主，它们探讨人的动物性和物质性。即所谓天生而来的本能、人体各功能的机制，以及与人体相关的各种化学成分、神经传导。这部分更偏重为什么，即人的行为、思想等等为什么会发生。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">而社会科学角度的心理学则有教育心理学、工程心理学、社会与个性心理学、犯罪学、临床心理学等等。它们关注个人、社会的行为和问题。它们可能更加务实一些，不考虑机制而着重现象及其解决方法。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">和许多学科一样，心理学的理论和应用部分并非完全对等。总有人会略带嘲讽地提及心理学的科学性，这不可回避，就像大多数人从来不把社会科学当科学一样。思维模式中科学的严谨、逻辑、不因人改变的印象与心理学的研究对象无法相融。当然，动物心理学也是有的。是不是觉得它更科学一点？<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;<\/p><h1>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">3. 心理学为什么算理科？还有涉及医学和社会人性方面的心理学有什么区别？<\/span><\/h1><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">心理学被定为理学是在基础心理学发展起来之后的界定。像早期的行为主义完全依靠实验，不管是观察猩猩、猴子还是观察人，都是严格地依照生物化学那一套来进行的。而再之前的弗洛伊德则以医师的形象出现更多一些。现在心理学的大块儿资金和研究都投在脑和认知科学里，也就是神经科学。只能说大家平日接触到的心理学就像真空中符合牛顿力学三定律的刚性小球一样，背后的东西还有很多。文、理、工学的分类未必是一个很好的分类方法，它的作用大概是延续初高中的文理分隔，给理科生一些被上帝选中的幻觉，给文科生一些质疑科学的鸡蛋。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">涉及医学的心理学主要是心理治疗。它的对象是有一定相似度的个体。&ldquo;社会人性&rdquo;，这个词所指的对象应该是社会人吧，它可能得出一些基于人本能的研究，诸如人的理性是有界限的，可能是一些描述性的统计结果（descriptive statistics） ，诸如性格、人格等等。涉及医学的心理学会更关注实际操作和医治效果，而涉及社会人性的心理学可能通过一系列很复杂的实验最后只是验证一个我们认为理所当然的结果。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;<\/p><h1>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">4. 我觉得心理学难以量化是硬伤%&hellip;&hellip;<\/span><\/h1><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">可以量化的。只是量化出来你们都不信罢了&hellip;&hellip;大家总觉得量表设计有问题，这些问题我这么填那么填完全是自己可控的，我希望出现什么结果就会出现什么结果。其实正式的量表有时候一套150道题目，做到后面本性都暴露了。。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">当然，像人格之类本身定义就很模糊，对于每一个量表，量表的制定者都有他明确的操作定义，因此不同的量表测出的人格可能不是一样的。就比如函数f的因变量有x,y,z，然而函数h的因变量有x,y,a。f和h都可以用来模拟一个人的人格，但是它们对人格的操作定义并不相同（因为它们的因变量不同，也就是测的东西不同）。和生活太贴近的东西，有时候就很难把它抽丝剥茧地分解开来，明确地定义a没有影响、x有影响。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;<\/p><h1>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">5. 心理系毕业后有什么就业方向<\/span><\/h1><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">额&hellip;&hellip;我只能很没想象力地罗列一些。心理咨询师、精神病医师（需要获得医学文凭貌似）、人力资源部、人因工程、各种老师、研究员、刑侦、咨询、职业培训师。<\/span><\/p><h1>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">6. 心理学有终极的研究方向之类的么, 比如物理学的终极方向是大统一理论这样的....&nbsp;<\/span><\/h1><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">心理学的终极问题都是哲学问题。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">比如：自由意志与决定论、感觉和现实的关系、唯心唯物等等。<\/span><\/p><h1>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">7. 心理學到底研究普遍心理現象，還是研究個人心理差異的不同表征？&nbsp;<\/span><\/h1><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">都有。前者是基于人群的研究，就是所谓群像。比如在火灾时候所有人作为一个整体的逃生策略是怎样的。后者是基于个体的统计，有的会做case study，有的是用因素分析之类的得出一个多维的评价。人格测试神马的就属于后一类。<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;<\/p><h1>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">8. 学心理的人会成为别人的&ldquo;垃圾桶&rdquo;吗？<\/span><\/h1><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 这分明要看你们怎么对待他们= =。。有些人不学心理也会被当成垃圾桶，有些人学了还是不会被当做垃圾桶。<\/span><\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <img src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn060\/20130127\/2125\/original_RvnT_1e1b00002ccc125b.jpg\" border=\"0\" thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn060\/20130127\/2125\/main_RvnT_1e1b00002ccc125b.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\"><\/p>","title":"Exploring Perception of Psychology - Q&amp;A","view":"159","textlength":"7411","comment":"22","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"0","time":"2013-01-27 12:08:35:000","text":"<p align=\"center\">    <strong>Results<\/strong><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Three dimensions were studied in the research: attitudes, opinions and reasons for them.<\/p><p align=\"left\">    <strong>1. Attitudes<\/strong><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This dimension split into two parts:<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 1. Attitudes and Majors<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2. Attitudes and Knowledge<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All of the data were collected through questionnaires.<\/p><p align=\"left\">    <em>&nbsp;<\/em><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <em>1.1 Attitudes and Majors<\/em><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <em>&nbsp;<img src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn064\/20130127\/1210\/original_EMk6_557d00001c5d1191.jpg\" border=\"0\" thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn064\/20130127\/1210\/main_EMk6_557d00001c5d1191.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\"><\/em><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;<\/p><p align=\"left\">    <img src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn064\/20130127\/1200\/original_MOXQ_690d00001c401190.jpg\" border=\"0\" thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn064\/20130127\/1200\/main_MOXQ_690d00001c401190.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\"><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;As was shown above, students from Science and Engineering department were inclined to take similar attitudes towards psychology, and Humanities students displayed some significant differences with Science and Engineering major participants. Because of the comparatively small gap between choices of grades, I defined p-value &lt; 0.1 as significant (I used 3 grades rather than 9 grades to test participants&rsquo; attitudes. It might be a mistake and should be improved next time.) The lower the p-value is, the higher possibility of differences between group A and B.<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <em>&nbsp;<\/em><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <em>1.2 Attitudes and Knowledge<\/em><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <em><img src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn065\/20130127\/1200\/original_h2xh_2c7c00000d05125d.jpg\" border=\"0\" thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn065\/20130127\/1200\/main_h2xh_2c7c00000d05125d.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\"><\/em><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;It was clear in the table above that taking part in psychology class and reading popular psychology books have no significant relation compared with those who didn&rsquo;t. Even though, it seems to make difference if one came across a few chapters in a psychology textbook. From the remarks some participants left on the questionnaire, I found that not all psychology classes they mentioned was professional and systematic. On the contrary, some classes were merely clich&eacute; and talked more about life than psychology itself. This might explain why taking psychology classes should not be the same as reading textbooks.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The attitude test revealed a positive correlation between students&rsquo; attitudes toward psychology and their majors. The impact of relevant knowledge was not that important in changing one&rsquo;s perception.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;<\/p><p align=\"left\">    <strong>2. Opinions<\/strong><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In this part, I concluded the opinions participants demonstrated both in interviews and questionnaires. Analysis was focused on the open-ended questions in the questionnaire.<\/p><p align=\"left\">    <em>2.1 Misconception: Psychology VS. Medicine<\/em><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <img src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn060\/20130127\/1200\/large_WcMq_33f100001c76118f.jpg\" border=\"0\" thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn060\/20130127\/1200\/main_WcMq_33f100001c76118f.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\"><\/p><p align=\"center\">Figure 2 Answers to what psychology major students should learn<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It was quite surprising that more people believed psychology should be a part of medicine than those who thought psychology students should learn to cure psychopath.&nbsp;<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;<\/p><p align=\"left\">    <em>2.2 Opinions<\/em><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The opinions collected in open-ended questions are listed below. The cues for content analysis were gathered during talks with senior students and teachers.<\/p><p align=\"left\">    <img src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn056\/20130127\/1200\/original_8isy_341100001c70118f.jpg\" border=\"0\" thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn056\/20130127\/1200\/main_8isy_341100001c70118f.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\"><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp; <\/span><img src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn060\/20130127\/1205\/large_a8ZQ_422d00001c74125c.jpg\" border=\"0\" thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn060\/20130127\/1205\/main_a8ZQ_422d00001c74125c.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\"><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">         <br>     <\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;It was quite clear from the figures above that a large proportion of opinions focused on whether psychology was scientific enough. The negative parts could approximately be summerized as a comparison with natural sciences. On the whole,&nbsp; most participants were reluctant to admit that psychology was science, and their scale of science was limited to natural science.<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <strong>3. Reasons<\/strong><\/p><p>The search for reasons were dependent on the content analysis of interviews. The participant from Math, Mechanical Engineering and Electronic Engineering all thought it unbelievable that psychology should belong to science rather than humanities. One of the participants was an idealism, and thus he believed what he trusted regardless of logic. While the other five participants showed an obvious trend of D&eacute;formation professionnelle.<\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">Math :<\/span><\/p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; It cannot prove itself.<\/p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Its theories are not <strong>rigorous<\/strong>.<\/p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; There are too many hypothesis and assumptions.<\/p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; Don&rsquo;t believe in chemistry, doubt some of physics, maths is the most reliable though sometimes it could also make mistakes on principles.<\/p><p align=\"left\">Mechanical Engineering :<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Behavior Psychology&nbsp; is <strong>useful<\/strong>.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Read what you think through words and behavior.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Personality analysis might help.<\/p><p align=\"left\">History :<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; It falls into <strong>Scientism<\/strong>.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Psychology is a method of making a lot of money these day.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; Psychology should keep its origin of Humanities.<\/p><p align=\"left\">Electrical Engineering :<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; A bit clich&eacute;, anyone knows what it was talking about.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; It&rsquo;s convincing but psychology doesn&rsquo;t provide<strong> practical<\/strong> ways to change the situation.<\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">         <br>     <\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Since most of the questionnaires were completed by students major in Sciences and Engineering, it again conform to the results I got in the attitudes part. Participants tend to look at psychology from the view of their own majors.<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-size: 14.0px;line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;In a nutshell, two results were concluded from the research.<\/span><\/p><p>(1) Whether one reads popular psychology books has nothing to do with his or her perception of psychology, while reading some psychology textbook did help to some extent.<\/p><p>(2) One&rsquo;s perception of psychology is correlated with his or her own major, but not significantly related to his knowledge of psychology, which might indicate a difference in way of thinking rather than merely knowledge accumulation.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;<\/p><p align=\"left\">    <strong>4. Bonus<\/strong><\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;I tried to gain access to some HRs and inquired about their comments on psycholoogy and students major in it.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1. Psychology is quite theoretical and not that empirical, so most psychology major students have difficiencies in the structure of knowledge needed in real working environment.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2. Some foreign-funded enterprises are willing to recruit a psychology major student in HR department, but it&rsquo;s hard to say the advantage of psychology students in career market.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3. Psychology can give useful models in ergonomics but it needs knowledge from other disciplines such as algorithm to give it power.<\/p><p align=\"left\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4. In the field of manufaturing and IT, psychology major students could help in HR department. They deal with relationship among employees and perform psychological measurements.<\/p><p align=\"left\">[THE END]<\/p><p align=\"left\">Just for fun~<\/p>","title":"Exploring Perception of Psychology - Results","view":"51","textlength":"9391","comment":"12","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"0","time":"2013-01-12 00:14:22:000","text":"<p align=\"center\">    <strong>Methods<\/strong><\/p><p>The research mainly consisted of three parts: interviews, questionnaires and data analysis. For the interview part, six participants were recruited from different departments in Tsinghua University through the Internet or the poster I put up in C building. Their majors and grades were listed below. As to questionnaires, 81 samples were collected through the Internet, of which 77 were valid. Three of the invalid ones were duplicates and the other one was not completed.<\/p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;<\/p><p align=\"center\">Table 1 Basic Information of Participants in the Interview<\/p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn062\/20130112\/0010\/original_cGSi_3b2f0000023b118d.jpg\" border=\"0\" thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn062\/20130112\/0010\/main_cGSi_3b2f0000023b118d.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\"><\/p><p>    <strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/p><p>    <strong>1. Pilot Study<\/strong><\/p><p>The first two participants were recruited for pilot study. By asking them questions and analyzed their responses, I found that my previous design was too abstract and they could not provide valid answers to it. For example, I intended to ask what did they think students major in psychology learned, however, they just kept silent for a few seconds and uttered three cold words, &rdquo;I don&rsquo;t know&rdquo; with a puzzled expression on their faces.<\/p><p>Furthermore, they also offered some aspects of misunderstanding in psychology. They did conform to my previous assumption that people might confuse psychologists with psychiatrists. It surprised me a bit that they both thought people who learned psychology could read others&rsquo; mind through behavior and words.<\/p><p>The most valuable enlightenment of the pilot study was the relation between their majors and perception of psychology. I had never realized the impact of one&rsquo;s major on his or her view of the outside world until I compared the words they used to describe their general comments on psychology. It strongly shocked me that there had been such an important factor underlying in the research.<\/p><p>And thus, I changed my plot of questions in the subsequent interviews and also designed my questionnaire based on the information I got in the pilot study. Most importantly, I switched my focus of research from &ldquo;what the perception is&rdquo; to &ldquo;why the perception is different&rdquo;, which means I don&rsquo;t need to completely rely on the papers that discussed the differences from a view of history but can actually prove it in the present.<\/p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<img src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn063\/20130112\/0010\/original_g5q0_2b1900000d161190.jpg\" border=\"0\" thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn063\/20130112\/0010\/main_g5q0_2b1900000d161190.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\"><\/p><p align=\"center\">&nbsp;<\/p><p align=\"center\">Figure 1 Distribution of Interviews according to their function<\/p><p>    <strong>&nbsp;<\/strong><\/p><p>    <strong>2. Questionnaire<\/strong><\/p><p>Based on the pilot study, I designed a questionnaire with 11 multiple choice questions and one open-ended question. The first two asked about majors and education background while the subsequent three questions inquired about subjects&rsquo; knowledge of psychology from both the academic aspect and popular psychology reading materials. The ninth was an attitude test, which asked subjects to grade how much they believed psychology was convincing. The questionnaire was not designed to be analyzed on a whole because the effect of learning from the choices could never be eliminated in such a question type. And thus, the data were not analyzed in the unit of question but on the basis of choices.<\/p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Four major aspects were analyzed:<\/p><p>a. The correlation between attitudes towards psychology and subjects&rsquo; majors.<\/p><p>b. The relation between one&rsquo;s knowledge of psychology and his or her attitudes toward it.<\/p><p>c. Whether psychology (or psychologists) and medical science (or psychiatrists) are confused<\/p><p>d. Answers in the open-ended question.<\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <strong>3. Data Analysis<\/strong><\/p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The possible correlations were analyzed by t-test, while interviews and open-ended questions mentioned above went through the process of content analysis. Both of them served as the potential resources in the explanation for the results.<\/p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The cues I used in content analysis were results of consulting my teachers and senior students. However, because of some inconvenience, no quantified reliability analysis was performed. Even though some of my friends had read through my coding and agreed on most of my coding cues. It could be further improved in the winter holiday.<\/p>","title":"Exploring Perception of Psychology and Its Formation-Methods","view":"58","textlength":"4957","comment":"7","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"0","time":"2012-12-24 23:43:53:000","text":"<p>URL：http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full<\/p><p>用清华的内网可以IP登陆的。外网不清楚&hellip;&hellip;贴到下面格式稍有些错乱。<\/p><h1>Science faculty&rsquo;s subtle gender biases favor male students<\/h1><p>    <ol>        <li>            <span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/search?author1=Corinne+A.+Moss-Racusin&sortspec=date&submit=Submit\">Corinne A. Moss-Racusin<\/a><\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#aff-1\"><sup>a<\/sup><\/a><span>,<\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#aff-2\"><sup>b<\/sup><\/a>, <\/li>        <li>            <span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/search?author1=John+F.+Dovidio&sortspec=date&submit=Submit\">John F. Dovidio<\/a><\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#aff-2\"><sup>b<\/sup><\/a>, <\/li>        <li>            <span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/search?author1=Victoria+L.+Brescoll&sortspec=date&submit=Submit\">Victoria L. Brescoll<\/a><\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#aff-4\"><sup>c<\/sup><\/a>, <\/li>        <li>            <span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/search?author1=Mark+J.+Graham&sortspec=date&submit=Submit\">Mark J. Graham<\/a><\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#aff-1\"><sup>a<\/sup><\/a><span>,<\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#aff-3\"><sup>d<\/sup><\/a>, and<\/li>        <li>            <span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/search?author1=Jo+Handelsman&sortspec=date&submit=Submit\">Jo Handelsman<\/a><\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#aff-1\"><sup>a<\/sup><\/a><span>,<\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#corresp-1\"><sup>1<\/sup><\/a>        <\/li>    <\/ol>    <p>        <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full\">Author Affiliations<\/a>    <\/p>    <ol>        <li>            <p>Edited<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#fn-5\">*<\/a> by Shirley Tilghman, Princeton University, Princeton, NJ, and approved August 21, 2012 (received for review July 2, 2012) <\/p>        <\/li>    <\/ol><\/p><p> <\/p><p>    <h2>Abstract<\/h2>    <p>Despite efforts to recruit and retain more women, a stark gender disparity persists within academic science. Abundant research has demonstrated gender bias in many demographic groups, but has yet to experimentally investigate whether science faculty exhibit a bias against female students that could contribute to the gender disparity in academic science. In a randomized double-blind study (<em>n<\/em> = 127), science faculty from research-intensive universities rated the application materials of a student&mdash;who was randomly assigned either a male or female name&mdash;for a laboratory manager position. Faculty participants rated the male applicant as significantly more competent and hireable than the (identical) female applicant. These participants also selected a higher starting salary and offered more career mentoring to the male applicant. The gender of the faculty participants did not affect responses, such that female and male faculty were equally likely to exhibit bias against the female student. Mediation analyses indicated that the female student was less likely to be hired because she was viewed as less competent. We also assessed faculty participants&rsquo; preexisting subtle bias against women using a standard instrument and found that preexisting subtle bias against women played a moderating role, such that subtle bias against women was associated with less support for the female student, but was unrelated to reactions to the male student. These results suggest that interventions addressing faculty gender bias might advance the goal of increasing the participation of women in science.<\/p><\/p><ul>    <li>        <span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/search?fulltext=diversity&sortspec=date&submit=Submit&andorexactfulltext=phrase\">diversity<\/a><\/span>    <\/li>     <li>        <span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/search?fulltext=lifestyle+choices&sortspec=date&submit=Submit&andorexactfulltext=phrase\">lifestyle choices<\/a><\/span>    <\/li>     <li>        <span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/search?fulltext=science+education&sortspec=date&submit=Submit&andorexactfulltext=phrase\">science education<\/a><\/span>    <\/li>     <li>        <span><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/search?fulltext=science+workforce&sortspec=date&submit=Submit&andorexactfulltext=phrase\">science workforce<\/a><\/span>    <\/li><\/ul><p>A 2012 report from the President&rsquo;s Council of Advisors on Science and Technology indicates that training scientists and engineers at current rates will result in a deficit of 1,000,000 workers to meet United States workforce demands over the next decade (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-1\">1<\/a>). To help close this formidable gap, the report calls for the increased training and retention of women, who are starkly underrepresented within many fields of science, especially among the professoriate (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-2\">2<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-3\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-4\">4<\/a>). Although the proportion of science degrees granted to women has increased (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-5\">5<\/a>), there is a persistent disparity between the number of women receiving PhDs and those hired as junior faculty (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-1\">1<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-2\">&dArr;<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-3\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-4\">4<\/a>). This gap suggests that the problem will not resolve itself solely by more generations of women moving through the academic pipeline but that instead, women&rsquo;s advancement within academic science may be actively impeded.<\/p><p>With evidence suggesting that biological sex differences in inherent aptitude for math and science are small or nonexistent (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-6\">6<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-7\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-8\">8<\/a>), the efforts of many researchers and academic leaders to identify causes of the science gender disparity have focused instead on the life choices that may compete with women&rsquo;s pursuit of the most demanding positions. Some research suggests that these lifestyle choices (whether free or constrained) likely contribute to the gender imbalance (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-9\">9<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-10\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-11\">11<\/a>), but because the majority of these studies are correlational, whether lifestyle factors are solely or primarily responsible remains unclear. Still, some researchers have argued that women&rsquo;s preference for nonscience disciplines and their tendency to take on a disproportionate amount of child- and family-care are the primary causes of the gender disparity in science (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-9\">9<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-10\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-11\">11<\/a>), and that it &ldquo;is not caused by discrimination in these domains&rdquo; (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-10\">10<\/a>). This assertion has received substantial attention and generated significant debate among the scientific community, leading some to conclude that gender discrimination indeed does not exist nor contribute to the gender disparity within academic science (e.g., refs. <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-12\">12<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-13\">13<\/a>).<\/p><p>Despite this controversy, experimental research testing for the presence and magnitude of gender discrimination in the biological and physical sciences has yet to be conducted. Although acknowledging that various lifestyle choices likely contribute to the gender imbalance in science (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-9\">9<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-10\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-11\">11<\/a>), the present research is unique in investigating whether faculty gender bias exists within academic biological and physical sciences, and whether it might exert an independent effect on the gender disparity as students progress through the pipeline to careers in science. Specifically, the present experiment examined whether, given an equally qualified male and female student, science faculty members would show preferential evaluation and treatment of the male student to work in their laboratory. Although the correlational and related laboratory studies discussed below suggest that such bias is likely (contrary to previous arguments) (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-9\">9<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-10\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-11\">11<\/a>), we know of no previous experiments that have tested for faculty bias against female students within academic science.<\/p><p>If faculty express gender biases, we are not suggesting that these biases are intentional or stem from a conscious desire to impede the progress of women in science. Past studies indicate that people&rsquo;s behavior is shaped by implicit or unintended biases, stemming from repeated exposure to pervasive cultural stereotypes (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-14\">14<\/a>) that portray women as less competent but simultaneously emphasize their warmth and likeability compared with men (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-15\">15<\/a>). Despite significant decreases in overt sexism over the last few decades (particularly among highly educated people) (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-16\">16<\/a>), these subtle gender biases are often still held by even the most egalitarian individuals (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-17\">17<\/a>), and are exhibited by both men and women (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-18\">18<\/a>). Given this body of work, we expected that female faculty would be just as likely as male faculty to express an unintended bias against female undergraduate science students. The fact that these prevalent biases often remain undetected highlights the need for an experimental investigation to determine whether they may be present within academic science and, if so, raise awareness of their potential impact.<\/p><p>Whether these gender biases operate in academic sciences remains an open question. On the one hand, although considerable research demonstrates gender bias in a variety of other domains (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-19\">19<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-20\">&dArr;<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-21\">&dArr;<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-22\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-23\">23<\/a>), science faculty members may not exhibit this bias because they have been rigorously trained to be objective. On the other hand, research demonstrates that people who value their objectivity and fairness are paradoxically particularly likely to fall prey to biases, in part because they are not on guard against subtle bias (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-24\">24<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-25\">25<\/a>). Thus, by investigating whether science faculty exhibit a bias that could contribute to the gender disparity within the fields of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (in which objectivity is emphasized), the current study addressed critical theoretical and practical gaps in that it provided an experimental test of faculty discrimination against female students within academic science.<\/p><p>A number of lines of research suggest that such discrimination is likely. Science is robustly male gender-typed (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-26\">26<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-27\">27<\/a>), resources are inequitably distributed among men and women in many academic science settings (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-28\">28<\/a>), some undergraduate women perceive unequal treatment of the genders within science fields (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-29\">29<\/a>), and nonexperimental evidence suggests that gender bias is present in other fields (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-19\">19<\/a>). Some experimental evidence suggests that even though evaluators report liking women more than men (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-15\">15<\/a>), they judge women as less competent than men even when they have identical backgrounds (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-20\">20<\/a>). However, these studies used undergraduate students as participants (rather than experienced faculty members), and focused on performance domains outside of academic science, such as completing perceptual tasks (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-21\">21<\/a>), writing nonscience articles (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-22\">22<\/a>), and being evaluated for a corporate managerial position (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-23\">23<\/a>).<\/p><p>Thus, whether aspiring women scientists encounter discrimination from faculty members remains unknown. The formative predoctoral years are a critical window, because students&rsquo; experiences at this juncture shape both their beliefs about their own abilities and subsequent persistence in science (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-30\">30<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-31\">31<\/a>). Therefore, we selected this career stage as the focus of the present study because it represents an opportunity to address issues that manifest immediately and also resurface much later, potentially contributing to the persistent faculty gender disparity (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-32\">32<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-33\">33<\/a>).<\/p><p>    <p>        <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#abstract-1\"><span>Previous Section<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-2\"><span>Next Section<\/span><\/a>    <\/p>    <h2>Current Study<\/h2>    <p>In addition to determining whether faculty expressed a bias against female students, we also sought to identify the processes contributing to this bias. To do so, we investigated whether faculty members&rsquo; perceptions of student competence would help to explain why they would be less likely to hire a female (relative to an identical male) student for a laboratory manager position. Additionally, we examined the role of faculty members&rsquo; preexisting subtle bias against women. We reasoned that pervasive cultural messages regarding women&rsquo;s lack of competence in science could lead faculty members to hold gender-biased attitudes that might subtly affect their support for female (but not male) science students. These generalized, subtly biased attitudes toward women could impel faculty to judge equivalent students differently as a function of their gender.<\/p>    <p>The present study sought to test for differences in faculty perceptions and treatment of equally qualified men and women pursuing careers in science and, if such a bias were discovered, reveal its mechanisms and consequences within academic science. We focused on hiring for a laboratory manager position as the primary dependent variable of interest because it functions as a professional launching pad for subsequent opportunities. As secondary measures, which are related to hiring, we assessed: (<em>i<\/em>) perceived student competence; (<em>ii<\/em>) salary offers, which reflect the extent to which a student is valued for these competitive positions; and (<em>iii<\/em>) the extent to which the student was viewed as deserving of faculty mentoring.<\/p>    <p>Our hypotheses were that: Science faculty&rsquo;s perceptions and treatment of students would reveal a gender bias favoring male students in perceptions of competence and hireability, salary conferral, and willingness to mentor (hypothesis A); Faculty gender would not influence this gender bias (hypothesis B); Hiring discrimination against the female student would be mediated (i.e., explained) by faculty perceptions that a female student is less competent than an identical male student (hypothesis C); and Participants&rsquo; preexisting subtle bias against women would moderate (i.e., impact) results, such that subtle bias against women would be negatively related to evaluations of the female student, but unrelated to evaluations of the male student (hypothesis D).<\/p><\/p><p>    <p>        <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-1\"><span>Previous Section<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-5\"><span>Next Section<\/span><\/a>    <\/p>    <h2>Results<\/h2>    <p>A broad, nationwide sample of biology, chemistry, and physics professors (<em>n<\/em> = 127) evaluated the application materials of an undergraduate science student who had ostensibly applied for a science laboratory manager position. All participants received the same materials, which were randomly assigned either the name of a male (<em>n<\/em> = 63) or a female (<em>n<\/em> = 64) student; student gender was thus the only variable that differed between conditions. Using previously validated scales, participants rated the student&rsquo;s competence and hireability, as well as the amount of salary and amount of mentoring they would offer the student. Faculty participants believed that their feedback would be shared with the student they had rated (see <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-7\"><em>Materials and Methods<\/em><\/a> for details).<\/p>    <p>        <h3>Student Gender Differences.<\/h3>         <p>The competence, hireability, salary conferral, and mentoring scales were each submitted to a two (student gender; male, female) &times; two (faculty gender; male, female) between-subjects ANOVA. In each case, the effect of student gender was significant (all <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.01), whereas the effect of faculty participant gender and their interaction was not (all <em>P<\/em> &gt; 0.19). Tests of simple effects (all <em>d<\/em> &gt; 0.60) indicated that faculty participants viewed the female student as less competent [<em>t<\/em>(125) = 3.89, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001] and less hireable [<em>t<\/em>(125) = 4.22, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001] than the identical male student (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#F1\">Fig. 1<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#T1\">Table 1<\/a>). Faculty participants also offered less career mentoring to the female student than to the male student [<em>t<\/em>(125) = 3.77,<em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001]. The mean starting salary offered the female student, $26,507.94, was significantly lower than that of $30,238.10 to the male student [<em>t<\/em>(124) = 3.42, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.01] (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#F2\">Fig. 2<\/a>). These results support hypothesis A.<\/p>        <p>            <p>                <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F1.expansion.html\"><img src=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F1.small.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Fig. 1.\"><\/a>                <p>                    <span>View larger version:<\/span>                    <ul>                        <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F1.expansion.html\">In this page<\/a>                        <\/li>                         <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F1.expansion.html\" target=\"_blank\">In a new window<\/a>                        <\/li>                    <\/ul>                    <ul>                        <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/powerpoint\/109\/41\/16474\/F1\">Download as PowerPoint Slide<\/a>                        <\/li>                    <\/ul>                <\/p>            <\/p>            <p>                <span>Fig. 1.<\/span>                <p>Competence, hireability, and mentoring by student gender condition (collapsed across faculty gender). All student gender differences are significant (<em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001). Scales range from 1 to 7, with higher numbers reflecting a greater extent of each variable. Error bars represent SEs. <em>n<\/em><sub>male<\/sub> <sub>student<\/sub> <sub>condition<\/sub> = 63, <em>n<\/em><sub>female<\/sub> <sub>student<\/sub> <sub>condition<\/sub>= 64.<\/p>                <p>                 <\/p>            <\/p>        <\/p>        <p>            <p>                <p>                    <span>View this table:<\/span>                    <ul>                        <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/T1.expansion.html\">In this window<\/a>                        <\/li>                         <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/T1.expansion.html\" target=\"_blank\">In a new window<\/a>                        <\/li>                    <\/ul>                <\/p>            <\/p>            <p>                <span>Table 1.<\/span>                <p>Means for student competence, hireability, mentoring and salary conferral by student gender condition and faculty gender<\/p>                <p>                 <\/p>            <\/p>        <\/p>        <p>            <p>                <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F2.expansion.html\"><img src=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F2.small.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Fig. 2.\"><\/a>                <p>                    <span>View larger version:<\/span>                    <ul>                        <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F2.expansion.html\">In this page<\/a>                        <\/li>                         <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F2.expansion.html\" target=\"_blank\">In a new window<\/a>                        <\/li>                    <\/ul>                    <ul>                        <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/powerpoint\/109\/41\/16474\/F2\">Download as PowerPoint Slide<\/a>                        <\/li>                    <\/ul>                <\/p>            <\/p>            <p>                <span>Fig. 2.<\/span>                <p>Salary conferral by student gender condition (collapsed across faculty gender). The student gender difference is significant (<em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.01). The scale ranges from $15,000 to $50,000. Error bars represent SEs. <em>n<\/em><sub>male<\/sub> <sub>student<\/sub> <sub>condition<\/sub>= 63, <em>n<\/em><sub>female<\/sub> <sub>student<\/sub> <sub>condition<\/sub> = 64.<\/p>                <p>                 <\/p>            <\/p>        <\/p>        <p>In support of hypothesis B, faculty gender did not affect bias (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#T1\">Table 1<\/a>). Tests of simple effects (all <em>d<\/em> &lt; 0.33) indicated that female faculty participants did not rate the female student as more competent [<em>t<\/em>(62) = 0.06, <em>P<\/em>= 0.95] or hireable [<em>t<\/em>(62) = 0.41, <em>P<\/em> = 0.69] than did male faculty. Female faculty also did not offer more mentoring [<em>t<\/em>(62) = 0.29, <em>P<\/em> = 0.77] or a higher salary [<em>t<\/em>(61) = 1.14, <em>P<\/em> = 0.26] to the female student than did their male colleagues. In addition, faculty participants&rsquo; scientific field, age, and tenure status had no effect (all <em>P<\/em> &gt; 0.53). Thus, the bias appears pervasive among faculty and is not limited to a certain demographic subgroup.<\/p>    <\/p>    <p>        <h3>Mediation and Moderation Analyses.<\/h3>         <p>Thus far, we have considered the results for competence, hireability, salary conferral, and mentoring separately to demonstrate the converging results across these individual measures. However, composite indices of measures that converge on an underlying construct are more statistically reliable, stable, and resistant to error than are each of the individual items (e.g., refs. <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-34\">34<\/a>and <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-35\">35<\/a>). Consistent with this logic, the established approach to measuring the broad concept of target competence typically used in this type of gender bias research is to standardize and average the competence scale items and the salary conferral variable to create one composite competence index, and to use this stable convergent measure for all analyses (e.g., refs. <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-36\">36<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-37\">37<\/a>). Because this approach obscures mean salary differences between targets, we chose to present salary as a distinct dependent variable up to this point, to enable a direct test of the potential discrepancy in salary offered to the male and female student targets. However, to rigorously examine the processes underscoring faculty gender bias, we reverted to standard practices at this point by averaging the standardized salary variable with the competence scale items to create a robust composite competence variable (α = 0.86). This composite competence variable was used in all subsequent mediation and moderation analyses.<\/p>        <p>Evidence emerged for hypothesis C, the predicted mediation (i.e., causal path; see <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods: Additional Analyses<\/em><\/a> for more information on mediation and the results of additional mediation analyses). The initially significant impact of student gender on hireability (β = &minus;0.35, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001) was reduced in magnitude and dropped to nonsignificance (β = &minus;0.10, <em>P<\/em> = 0.13) after accounting for the impact of student composite competence (which was a strong predictor, β = 0.69, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001), Sobel&rsquo;s <em>Z<\/em> = 3.94, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001 (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#F3\">Fig. 3<\/a>). This pattern of results provides evidence for full mediation, indicating that the female student was less likely to be hired than the identical male because she was viewed as less competent overall.<\/p>        <p>            <p>                <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F3.expansion.html\"><img src=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F3.small.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Fig. 3.\"><\/a>                <p>                    <span>View larger version:<\/span>                    <ul>                        <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F3.expansion.html\">In this page<\/a>                        <\/li>                         <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474\/F3.expansion.html\" target=\"_blank\">In a new window<\/a>                        <\/li>                    <\/ul>                    <ul>                        <li>                            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/powerpoint\/109\/41\/16474\/F3\">Download as PowerPoint Slide<\/a>                        <\/li>                    <\/ul>                <\/p>            <\/p>            <p>                <span>Fig. 3.<\/span>                <p>Student gender difference hiring mediation. Values are standardized regression coefficients. The value in parentheses reflects a bivariate analysis. The dashed line represents the mediated path. The composite student competence variable consists of the averaged standardized salary variable and the competence scale items. Student gender is coded such that male = 0, female = 1. <em>n<\/em><sub>male<\/sub> <sub>student<\/sub> <sub>condition<\/sub> = 63, <em>n<\/em><sub>female<\/sub> <sub>student<\/sub><sub>condition<\/sub> = 64. ***<em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001.<\/p>                <p>                 <\/p>            <\/p>        <\/p>        <p>We also conducted moderation analysis (i.e., testing for factors that could amplify or attenuate the demonstrated effect) to determine the impact of faculty participants&rsquo; preexisting subtle bias against women on faculty participants&rsquo; perceptions and treatment of male and female science students (see <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods: Additional Analyses<\/em><\/a> for more information on and the results of additional moderation analyses). For this purpose, we administered the Modern Sexism Scale (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-38\">38<\/a>), a well-validated instrument frequently used for this purpose (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods<\/em><\/a>). Consistent with our intentions, this scale measures unintentional negativity toward women, as contrasted with a more blatant form of conscious hostility toward women.<\/p>        <p>Results of multiple regression analyses indicated that participants&rsquo; preexisting subtle bias against women significantly interacted with student gender to predict perceptions of student composite competence (β = &minus;0.39, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.01), hireability (β = &minus;0.31, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.05), and mentoring (β = &minus;0.55, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001). To interpret these significant interactions, we examined the simple effects separately by student gender. Results revealed that the more preexisting subtle bias participants exhibited against women, the less composite competence (β = &minus;0.36, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.01) and hireability (β = &minus;0.39, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.01) they perceived in the female student, and the less mentoring (β = &minus;0.53, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001) they were willing to offer her. In contrast, faculty participants&rsquo; levels of preexisting subtle bias against women were unrelated to the perceptions of the male student&rsquo;s composite competence (β = 0.16, <em>P<\/em> = 0.22) and hireability (β = 0.07, <em>P<\/em> = 0.59), and the amount of mentoring (β = 0.22,<em>P<\/em> = 0.09) they were willing to offer him. [Although this effect is marginally significant, its direction suggests that faculty participants&rsquo; preexisting subtle bias against women may actually have made them more inclined to mentor the male student relative to the female student (although this effect should be interpreted with caution because of its marginal significance).] Thus, it appears that faculty participants&rsquo; preexisting subtle gender bias undermined support for the female student but was unrelated to perceptions and treatment of the male student. These findings support hypothesis D.<\/p>        <p>Finally, using a previously validated scale, we also measured how much faculty participants liked the student (see <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods<\/em><\/a>). In keeping with a large body of literature (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-15\">15<\/a>), faculty participants reported liking the female (mean = 4.35, SD = 0.93) more than the male student [(mean = 3.91, SD = 0.1.08), <em>t<\/em>(125) = &minus;2.44, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.05]. However, consistent with this previous literature, liking the female student more than the male student did not translate into positive perceptions of her composite competence or material outcomes in the form of a job offer, an equitable salary, or valuable career mentoring. Moreover, only composite competence (and not likeability) helped to explain why the female student was less likely to be hired; in mediation analyses, student gender condition (β = &minus;0.48, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001) remained a strong predictor of hireability along with likeability (β = 0.60, <em>P<\/em> &lt; 0.001). These findings underscore the point that faculty participants did not exhibit outright hostility or dislike toward female students, but were instead affected by pervasive gender stereotypes, unintentionally downgrading the competence, hireability, salary, and mentoring of a female student compared with an identical male.<\/p>    <\/p><\/p><p>    <p>        <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-2\"><span>Previous Section<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-6\"><span>Next Section<\/span><\/a>    <\/p>    <h2>Discussion<\/h2>    <p>The present study is unique in investigating subtle gender bias on the part of faculty in the biological and physical sciences. It therefore informs the debate on possible causes of the gender disparity in academic science by providing unique experimental evidence that science faculty of both genders exhibit bias against female undergraduates. As a controlled experiment, it fills a critical gap in the existing literature, which consisted only of experiments in other domains (with undergraduate students as participants) and correlational data that could not conclusively rule out the influence of other variables.<\/p>    <p>Our results revealed that both male and female faculty judged a female student to be less competent and less worthy of being hired than an identical male student, and also offered her a smaller starting salary and less career mentoring. Although the differences in ratings may be perceived as modest, the effect sizes were all moderate to large (<em>d<\/em> = 0.60&ndash;0.75). Thus, the current results suggest that subtle gender bias is important to address because it could translate into large real-world disadvantages in the judgment and treatment of female science students (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-39\">39<\/a>). Moreover, our mediation findings shed light on the processes responsible for this bias, suggesting that the female student was less likely to be hired than the male student because she was perceived as less competent. Additionally, moderation results indicated that faculty participants&rsquo; preexisting subtle bias against women undermined their perceptions and treatment of the female (but not the male) student, further suggesting that chronic subtle biases may harm women within academic science. Use of a randomized controlled design and established practices from audit study methodology support the ecological validity and educational implications of our findings (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods<\/em><\/a>).<\/p>    <p>It is noteworthy that female faculty members were just as likely as their male colleagues to favor the male student. The fact that faculty members&rsquo; bias was independent of their gender, scientific discipline, age, and tenure status suggests that it is likely unintentional, generated from widespread cultural stereotypes rather than a conscious intention to harm women (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-17\">17<\/a>). Additionally, the fact that faculty participants reported liking the female more than the male student further underscores the point that our results likely do not reflect faculty members&rsquo; overt hostility toward women. Instead, despite expressing warmth toward emerging female scientists, faculty members of both genders appear to be affected by enduring cultural stereotypes about women&rsquo;s lack of science competence that translate into biases in student evaluation and mentoring.<\/p>    <p>Our careful selection of expert participants revealed gender discrimination among existing science faculty members who interact with students on a regular basis (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods: Subjects and Recruitment Strategy<\/em><\/a>). This method allowed for a high degree of ecological validity and generalizability relative to an approach using nonexpert participants, such as other undergraduates or lay people unfamiliar with laboratory manager job requirements and academic science mentoring (i.e., the participants in much psychological research on gender discrimination). The results presented here reinforce those of Stenpries, Anders, and Ritzke (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-40\">40<\/a>), the only other experiment we know of that recruited faculty participants. Because this previous experiment also indicated bias within academic science, its results raised serious concerns about the potential for faculty bias within the biological and physical sciences, casting further doubt on assertions (based on correlational data) that such biases do not exist (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-9\">9<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-10\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-11\">11<\/a>). In the Steinpreis et al. experiment, psychologists were more likely to hire a psychology faculty job applicant when the applicant&rsquo;s curriculum vitae was assigned a male (rather than female) name (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-40\">40<\/a>). This previous work invited a study that would extend the finding to faculty in the biological and physical sciences and to reactions to undergraduates, whose competence was not already fairly established by accomplishments associated with the advanced career status of the faculty target group of the previous study. By providing this unique investigation of faculty bias against female students in biological and physical sciences, the present study extends past work to a critical early career stage, and to fields where women&rsquo;s underrepresentation remains stark (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-2\">2<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-3\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-4\">4<\/a>).<\/p>    <p>Indeed, our findings raise concerns about the extent to which negative predoctoral experiences may shape women&rsquo;s subsequent decisions about persistence and career specialization. Following conventions established in classic experimental studies to create enough ambiguity to leave room for potentially biased responses (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-20\">20<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-23\">23<\/a>), the student applicants in the present research were described as qualified to succeed in academic science (i.e., having coauthored a publication after obtaining 2 y of research experience), but not irrefutably excellent. As such, they represented a majority of aspiring scientists, and were precisely the type of students most affected by faculty judgments and mentoring (see <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods<\/em><\/a> for more discussion). Our results raise the possibility that not only do such women encounter biased judgments of their competence and hireability, but also receive less faculty encouragement and financial rewards than identical male counterparts. Because most students depend on feedback from their environments to calibrate their own worth (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-41\">41<\/a>), faculty&rsquo;s assessments of students&rsquo; competence likely contribute to students&rsquo; self-efficacy and goal setting as scientists, which may influence decisions much later in their careers. Likewise, inasmuch as the advice and mentoring that students receive affect their ambitions and choices, it is significant that the faculty in this study were less inclined to mentor women than men. This finding raises the possibility that women may opt out of academic science careers in part because of diminished competence judgments, rewards, and mentoring received in the early years of the careers. In sum, the predoctoral years represent a window during which students&rsquo; experiences of faculty bias or encouragement are particularly likely to shape their persistence in academic science (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-30\">30<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-31\">&dArr;<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-32\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-33\">33<\/a>). Thus, the present study not only fills an important gap in the research literature, but also has critical implications for pressing social and educational issues associated with the gender disparity in science.<\/p>    <p>If women&rsquo;s decisions to leave science fields when or before they reach the faculty level are influenced by unequal treatment by undergraduate advisors, then existing efforts to create more flexible work settings (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-42\">42<\/a>) or increase women&rsquo;s identification with science (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-27\">27<\/a>) may not fully alleviate a critical underlying problem. Our results suggest that academic policies and mentoring interventions targeting undergraduate advisors could contribute to reducing the gender disparity. Future research should evaluate the efficacy of educating faculty and students about the existence and impact of bias within academia, an approach that has reduced racial bias among students (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-43\">43<\/a>). Educational efforts might address research on factors that attenuate gender bias in real-world settings, such as increasing women&rsquo;s self-monitoring (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-44\">44<\/a>). Our results also point to the importance of establishing objective, transparent student evaluation and admissions criteria to guard against observers&rsquo; tendency to unintentionally use different standards when assessing women relative to men (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-45\">45<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-46\">46<\/a>). Without such actions, faculty bias against female undergraduates may continue to undermine meritocratic advancement, to the detriment of research and education.<\/p><\/p><p>    <p>        <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-5\"><span>Previous Section<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-7\"><span>Next Section<\/span><\/a>    <\/p>    <h2>Conclusions<\/h2>    <p>The dearth of women within academic science reflects a significant wasted opportunity to benefit from the capabilities of our best potential scientists, whether male or female. Although women have begun to enter some science fields in greater numbers (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-5\">5<\/a>), their mere increased presence is not evidence of the absence of bias. Rather, some women may persist in academic science despite the damaging effects of unintended gender bias on the part of faculty. Similarly, it is not yet possible to conclude that the preferences for other fields and lifestyle choices (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-9\">9<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-10\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-11\">11<\/a>) that lead many women to leave academic science (even after obtaining advanced degrees) are not themselves influenced by experiences of bias, at least to some degree. To the extent that faculty gender bias impedes women&rsquo;s full participation in science, it may undercut not only academic meritocracy, but also the expansion of the scientific workforce needed for the next decade&rsquo;s advancement of national competitiveness (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-1\">1<\/a>).<\/p><\/p><p>    <p>        <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-6\"><span>Previous Section<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ack-1\"><span>Next Section<\/span><\/a>    <\/p>    <h2>Materials and Methods<\/h2>    <p>        <h3>Participants.<\/h3>         <p>We recruited faculty participants from Biology, Chemistry, and Physics departments at three public and three private large, geographically diverse research-intensive universities in the United States, strategically selected for their representative characteristics (see <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods<\/em><\/a> for more information on department selection). The demographics of the 127 respondents corresponded to both the averages for the selected departments and faculty at all United States research-intensive institutions, meeting the criteria for generalizability even from nonrandom samples (see <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods<\/em><\/a> for more information on recruitment strategy and participant characteristics). Indeed, we were particularly careful to obtain a sample representative of the underlying population, because many past studies have demonstrated that when this is the case, respondents and nonrespondents typically do not differ on demographic characteristics and responses to focal variables (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-47\">47<\/a>).<\/p>        <p>Additionally, in keeping with recommended practices, we conducted an a priori power analysis before beginning data collection to determine the optimal sample size needed to detect effects without biasing results toward obtaining significance (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods: Subjects and Recruitment Strategy<\/em><\/a>) (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-48\">48<\/a>). Thus, although our sample size may appear small to some readers, it is important to note that we obtained the necessary power and representativeness to generalize from our results while purposefully avoiding an unnecessarily large sample that could have biased our results toward a false-positive type I error (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-48\">48<\/a>).<\/p>    <\/p>    <p>        <h3>Procedure.<\/h3>         <p>Participants were asked to provide feedback on the materials of an undergraduate science student who stated their intention to go on to graduate school, and who had recently applied for a science laboratory manager position. Of importance, participants believed they were evaluating a real student who would subsequently receive the faculty participants&rsquo; ratings as feedback to help their career development (see <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods<\/em><\/a> for more information, and <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=SF1\" target=\"_blank\">Fig. S1<\/a> for the full text of the cover story). Thus, the faculty participants&rsquo; ratings were associated with definite consequences.<\/p>        <p>Following established practices, the laboratory manager application was designed to reflect high but slightly ambiguous competence, allowing for variability in participant responses (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-20\">20<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-23\">23<\/a>). In addition, a promising but still-nascent applicant is precisely the type of student whose persistence in academic science is most likely to be affected by faculty support or discouragement (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-30\">30<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-31\">&dArr;<\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-32\">&dArr;<\/a>&ndash;<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-33\">33<\/a>), rendering faculty reactions to such a student of particular interest for the present purposes. The materials were developed in consultation with a panel of academic science researchers (who had extensive experience hiring and supervising student research assistants) to ensure that they would be perceived as realistic (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Materials and Methods<\/em><\/a>). Results of a funneled debriefing (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-49\">49<\/a>) indicated that this was successful; no participant reported suspicions that the target was not an actual student who would receive their evaluation.<\/p>        <p>Participants were randomly assigned to one of two student gender conditions: application materials were attributed to either a male student (John, <em>n<\/em> = 63), or a female student (Jennifer, <em>n<\/em> = 64), two names that have been pretested as equivalent in likability and recognizeability (<a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-50\">50<\/a>). Thus, each participant saw only one set of materials, from either the male or female applicant (see <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=SF2\" target=\"_blank\">Fig. S2<\/a> for the full text of the laboratory manager application and <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\/pnas.201211286SI.pdf?targetid=nameddest=STXT\" target=\"_blank\"><em>SI Method and Materials<\/em><\/a> for more information on all materials). Because all other information was held constant between conditions, any differences in participants&rsquo; responses are attributable to the gender of the student. Using validated scales, participants rated student competence, their own likelihood of hiring the student, selected an annual starting salary for the student, indicated how much career mentoring they would provide to such a student, and completed the Modern Sexism Scale.<\/p>    <\/p><\/p><p>    <p>        <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#sec-7\"><span>Previous Section<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#fn-group-1\"><span>Next Section<\/span><\/a>    <\/p>    <h2>Acknowledgments<\/h2>    <p>We thank faculty members from six anonymous universities for their involvement as participants; and Jessamina Blum, John Crosnick, Jennifer Frederick, Jaime Napier, Jojanneke van der Toorn, Tiffany Tsang, Tessa West, James Young, and two anonymous reviewers for valuable input. This research was supported by a grant from the Howard Hughes Medical Institute Professors Program (to J.H.).<\/p><\/p><p>    <p>        <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ack-1\"><span>Previous Section<\/span><\/a><a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#ref-list-1\"><span>Next Section<\/span><\/a>    <\/p>    <h2>Footnotes<\/h2>    <ul>        <li>            <sup>1<\/sup>To whom correspondence should be addressed. E-mail: <a href=\"mailto:jo.handelsman@yale.edu\">jo.handelsman@yale.edu<\/a>.<\/li>    <\/ul>    <ul>        <li>            <p>Author contributions: C.A.M.-R., J.F.D., V.L.B., M.J.G., and J.H. designed research; C.A.M.-R. performed research; C.A.M.-R. analyzed data; and C.A.M.-R., J.F.D., V.L.B., M.J.G., and J.H. wrote the paper.<\/p>        <\/li>        <li>            <p>The authors declare no conflict of interest.<\/p>        <\/li>        <li>            <p>*This Direct Submission article had a prearranged editor.<\/p>        <\/li>        <li>            <p>This article contains supporting information online at <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental\" target=\"_blank\">www.pnas.org\/lookup\/suppl\/doi:10.1073\/pnas.1211286109\/-\/DCSupplemental<\/a>.<\/p>        <\/li>    <\/ul><\/p><p>    <p>Freely available online through the PNAS open access option.<\/p><\/p><p>    <p>        <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.full#fn-group-1\"><span>Previous Section<\/span><\/a>        <p>         <\/p>    <\/p>    <h2>References<\/h2>    <ol>        <li>            <a href=\"http:\/\/www.pnas.org\/content\/109\/41\/16474.fu