{"share":"1","time":"2012-12-17 00:30:06:000","text":"<p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">In the first place, all participants are presumed to have a general knowledge of psychology, which includes familiarity with the term itself and other related ones that might come along.<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">It must not be regarded as a rigorous test of public perception of psychology because of its restrained volume of participants and their similar educational background.<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">I intend to construct a complete series of questions concerning the most asked aspects of the psychology major. For example, what do students major in psychology learn? What will they possibly do after graduation? Do you believe in psychological research? However, questions that asked about career path and future space of development are not actually designed for analysis. They serve to form a seemingly coherent flow of thoughts that supports the whole questionnaire. That is to say, those questions are irrelevant items in this test.<\/span><\/p><p align=\"left\">    <span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">As to the general voice of the questionnaire, it can be argued that this test was not presented in a neutral stand, and a slightly passive voice in the instructions and options may influence the participants reply and thus cause a \"biased response\". In fact, I was quite sure that most of the participants taking part in the survey would be my friends because I sent out links of the questionnaire through www.RenRen.com. They might choose what they should think but not what they actually think because of our familiarity even though they remain anonymous in the questionnaire.<\/span><\/p><p>    <span style=\"font-family: Times New Roman;\">Finally, the irrelevant items are just for confusion, and I should write them in a seemingly formal way but never reveal too much truth to my participants. If I formally list what psychology major students will study in their four-year college education, participants will easily choose all those options since they all sound proper after some consideration. It&rsquo;s similar to asking what is paper used for and giving options like writing and paper plane. We all know paper is used for writing and it&rsquo;s our instinct reaction, while no one will deny its contribution in making a paper plane though it&rsquo;s what the option teaches us. For this purpose, I should only compose my options in a weird manner and carefully avoid my smart participants learning from them~<\/span><img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/imgpro\/emotions\/tie\/2.gif?ver=1\" border=\"0\" alt=\"谄笑\"><img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/imgpro\/emotions\/tie\/4.gif?ver=1\" border=\"0\" alt=\"调皮\"><\/p>","title":"Is the questionnaire biased?","view":"72","textlength":"2820","comment":"14","access":"0","type":"0"}
