{"share":"1","time":"2012-11-26 22:38:43:000","text":"<p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>长久不写东西，笔显得生疏。<\/p><p>高三的时候叫嚣着从小到大在一个地方读书多没意思，高二的时候随笔无聊了就黑一黑魔都。到北京四个多月了，日子也就和着暖气哄闹起来了。那天读写4的课上讲culture shock，说the first stage is honeymoon, then comes depression，然后又说参加过orientation 辅导的会出现更强烈的homesick症状。随后各种抨击四阶段理论，说没有empirical evidence。（忽视我语言切换紊乱）<\/p><p>倒觉得这描绘和我的感觉挺像，虽然没什么homesick，但压抑总是有的。起初一穷二白什么都不知道，在学校里天天都跟探险一样。今天发现了个教学楼，进去转转，明天发现了个纪念碑，过去看看。中午出个太阳都能高兴老半天，大概是巅峰体验的阈值太低。后来逐渐冷清，发现其实相比之下魔都还是相当不错的。倘若规规矩矩地过日子，生活其实可以过得很单调。早上出寝室，去六教或三教或四教或图书馆。在清芬吃午饭，然后上课、自习，阳光长跑、吃饭、洗澡。耐着性子一件一件地码完日程本上的故事实在有些抵牾天性。总会无意发现一篇好文章，抱着电脑在教室慢慢悠悠、一字一句地读；吃个早饭刷刷豆瓣，看着那些木头、阳光、石头、玻璃错杂地唱着弥撒，心驰神往，呛了一口豆浆；竟然会无聊地一遍一遍调了6个多小时数据库，改字体、字号、按钮前景色、悬停前景色、按下前景色，好像不把默认界面斩草除根以除后患就没法通向美丽新世界；甚至会心血来潮，像今晚这样，窝在寝室码一串没什么大意思的小字。普心提到直觉和分析思维的启动机制和情景，掐指一算，其实大多数时候会体谅前者，大概那永远是个长不大的小孩，想想小孩嘛，让让它吧。多数时候并不在乎效率多高，生活过得多紧张。毕竟不做社工不加社团，只想补补高中三年落下的书。只要时间溜之前跟我打声招呼，别一声不吭就跑了。<\/p><p>还是要赞美一下图书馆，虽然并不是所有书都能在图书馆或电子书数据库里找到，尤其是那些尚没有译本的原著，这是个大遗憾。最近被很多实验纠缠着，要看的书也积成了三座小山，横看竖看竟然还不是同样的山，颇感忧伤。做个reference的列表做了大半个下午，时间你要真是个维度就跟z轴一样别动吧。免得我总得踮着脚尖扯你那还没转过弯的尾巴。<\/p><p>生活还是很happy的，不用怎么刷题。光这一点就足够让高三的我羡慕嫉妒恨了。虽然没了答案的世界少了很多争执，但却一天到晚挂着一副狐疑的表情。<\/p><p>大概最坚定的只有思修老师了。<\/p>","title":"随记 11.26","view":"72","textlength":"1089","comment":"1","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"8","time":"2012-11-24 00:41:42:000","text":"<p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <strong>袁欣晨<\/strong>：&ldquo;生日快乐！跟施阮好好处！&rdquo;<\/p><p>    <strong>贾璐琦<\/strong>：咳咳： 生日快乐！成年更快乐！看到你画的作业各种羡慕啊&gt;&lt; 不过一定也很辛苦&hellip;&hellip;祝什么呢？先是不要感冒~&ldquo;为祖国健康工作五十年&rdquo;<img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/imgpro\/emotions\/tie\/4.gif?ver=1\" border=\"0\" alt=\"调皮\">。还要一直能和喜欢的人在一起，一直能做喜欢的事！我正在策划寒假来看你们~ 开心滴等我来<img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/imgpro\/emotions\/tie\/20.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"吻\"><\/p><p>    <strong>于戴维<\/strong>：主席成人快乐~欢迎常来后花园游玩~<\/p><p>    <strong>陈童<\/strong>：好想再回到那些年的时光，回到教室座位前后，故意讨你温柔的骂。&hellip;&hellip;桑捏夸落（上海话生日快乐）<\/p><p>    <strong>钮亦驰<\/strong>：成年快乐！不用跟学生会&ldquo;作对&rdquo;的感觉真好~<\/p><p>    <strong>姚晨立<\/strong>：沙神，主席，生日快乐！你终于也跟我们一样是成年人了，虽然你比我成熟&hellip;好吧&hellip;在帝都请继续牛逼，照顾好自己。我们在家乡等你。Ps：你还欠我情侣杯。再不送我都要分手了TAT<\/p><p>你终究还是太年轻了&mdash;&mdash;刚睡醒的徐庆韬说的<\/p><p>    <strong>於慧龄<\/strong>：主席生日快乐~18了呢~你是我见过的最优秀最完美的女生^ ^在清华的学习一定很累吧，还是这句话，紧张学习的时候也要注意保重身体哦~别的不多说啦~快乐快乐~<\/p><p>    <strong>许文<\/strong>：敬爱的沙神生日快乐。。自己的目标都能实现。。加油叭。。开心就好。。。（要求慧龄整合成一条~）<\/p><p>    <strong>张乃卿<\/strong>：祝沙神成年快乐！！你永远是我们心中最boss的沙主席~~<\/p><p>    <strong>孙晨路<\/strong>：生日快乐~~成年快乐！！！前后座的日子好怀念~~<\/p><p>    <strong>陈心怡<\/strong>：生日快乐!!和施阮好好过日子哟XD<\/p><p>    <strong>王安舒<\/strong>：沙烨星 啥也行〜生日快乐哦&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <strong>赵辕尊<\/strong>：祝贺主席成年！还真是真是年少成大器。上次散伙饭我说你是我极崇拜的人可不是酒后乱说，祝继续在马路对面逆天。&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <strong>谭庆俞<\/strong>：18岁的生日我们大多已走过，当这一天终于属于你的时候，你会发现，你是幸福的：有这么多好朋友悄悄留下几句祝福，还有很多人叫你一声&ldquo;沙神&rdquo;<\/p><p>    <strong>杨立安<\/strong>：膜拜大主席。。以前觉得你只是读书牛B现在果断发现谈恋爱也牛B啊。。。从此中国成年人的队伍又壮大了起来。。。啊哈哈哈。。。祝主席幸福快乐每一天。。吃好喝好睡好恋爱谈好考试考好。。。嗯。。就这样<\/p><p>    <strong>余文豪<\/strong>：虽然只有几个月的时间，不过仍旧被你的人格魅力所折服。。。也许我并不了解你，但我希望你能成为第二个林徽因<\/p><p>    <strong>王斯傲<\/strong>：:\"I love u 4ever~\" it's my word for her（注：博爱的童鞋）<\/p><p>    <strong>许逸灵<\/strong>：在这举国欢庆的日子，只有深深祝福：年年有今日，岁岁有今朝。为我们留下更美的背影。<\/p><p>    <strong>石垠<\/strong>：主席&hellip;和施软要好好地，不用担心假逼，他在香港，要相信异地恋是不靠谱的&hellip;<\/p><p>    <strong>李吉妍<\/strong>：<\/p><p>亲爱的星~~~生日快乐！<\/p><p>&nbsp;你终于成年啦~~~（原来你以前一直未成年呀，我怎么都没感觉）<\/p><p>从此以后你就可以光明正大去ktv（好像之前没去过一样）<\/p><p>打游戏不用防沉迷（貌似你也不打游戏）<\/p><p>可以入党了（咦，我居然会想到这个）<\/p><p>可以喝酒了（不行不行，酒还是少喝）<\/p><p>（这成年成得怎么这么没意义？）<\/p><p>不不不，怎么能说是没意义，这是思想上的跨越，时空上的突破，人类发展史上的里程碑！（不好意思，拿错稿子了）<\/p><p>Anyway，虽然感觉成年这个概念已经越来越水了，但星的生日当然是大事中的大事！<\/p><p>虽然咱们现在是异地（好心酸T^T)，但一大波来自王子的祝福正在向你袭来，（咳咳，我要正经了）祝身体健康，心情舒畅，学业顺利，感情美满，总之就是&mdash;&mdash;万事如意！(感觉这个超万能的！）<\/p><p>礼物咱就不送了（我怎么这么无耻&gt;&lt;），最后用汤姆猫的声音高歌一曲：<\/p><p>Happy birthday to you~<\/p><p>Happy birthday to you~<\/p><p>Happy birthday to little star~<\/p><p>Happy birthday to you~<\/p><p>(谢谢，谢谢大家的掌声...&amp;%$*##$%#@#$^%#$@...直接被轰下台...）<\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <strong>吴大伟<\/strong>：生日快乐！三年来我们在上中共同度过了一段美好的时光，这段时光将是你我心底永远的慰藉。现在我们各自追逐自己的梦想，只有为此全身心地投入，你我才能找到短暂生命的不朽价值；我们也不再像过去一样身处一个紧密的集体中，但在人与人的爱中你我能获得幸福，在对世界践行责任的过程中我们的心灵才完整。人的一生从来不可能一帆风顺，但我们最痛苦的时候恰恰是我们成长最快的时候，也只有经历痛苦我们才能真正感受喜悦、幸福与价值。加油吧！<\/p><p>    <strong>毛俊喆<\/strong>：心儿要永远憧憬着未来，尽管闭上眼睛时，有闪耀的树叶，有歌唱的和声，有灵魂的香味。成年快乐！<\/p><p>    <strong>顾天猷<\/strong>：沙神，进了复旦之后我才越发感觉到你在学习和工作上的能力是如此强大，此处膜拜一下，求保佑各科安过。废话结束！祝你18岁生日快乐，于今成人，更能有大作为，也便日后我等逢人可吹嘘同学一场(^_^)。再祝学业顺利，万事如意。感情美满，往昔玩笑（喂喂。。你知道那是被黑出翔的节奏），通通忘记！<\/p><p>    <strong>丁开心<\/strong>：主席大人~跟某人抢零点这种无节操的事情我猜不屑干嘞~不过果断还是该挤在前排~~生日快乐啦~~下次聚会别再缺席哈，人民群众翘首期盼~~<img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/imgpro\/emotions\/tie\/4.gif?ver=1\" border=\"0\" alt=\"调皮\"><img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/imgpro\/emotions\/tie\/4.gif?ver=1\" border=\"0\" alt=\"调皮\"><\/p><p>    <strong>刘甦璟<\/strong>：谢谢你在极其繁忙的时候帮我补语文，补英语，祝你大学天天快乐~<\/p><p>    <strong>黄之颖<\/strong>：<span>万能的主席，生日快乐！！等了好久终于迎来你的十八岁啦\\(^o^)\/是不是很兴奋呢？？很幸运能和你在SHS一起在学生会奋斗两年，这也是我记忆中最美好的时光了吧。虽然没有和你在一个部门，但也真实地感受到了你的魅力：理性，睿智，卓越的口才还有真情。然后是祝福啦：祝身体健康，1500轻松过，学业蒸蒸日上，爱情甜蜜美满*^O^*生日快乐(^_^)<\/span><\/p><p>    <span><strong>张锐峰<\/strong>：生日快乐~幸福美满~<\/span><\/p><p>    <span><strong>王琰宁<\/strong>：<span>总觉得很久没有见过，也很久没有说过话了。在人人上看了你最近的作品，更是叹为观止。主席还是一如既往地威武霸气，令人仰视。我觉得不需要祝愿，只用坚信，主席一定能走得很远很高~生日快乐小沙~<\/span><\/span><\/p><p>    <span><span><strong>尤戌尘<\/strong>：致沙同学：你都成人了哈！十分怀念坐在你后面的日子！祝十八岁生日快乐~<\/span><\/span><\/p><p>    <span><span><strong>袁鸿杰<\/strong>：<span>生日快乐，祝风采依旧，成为清华建筑的boss~<\/span><\/span><\/span><\/p><p>    <span><span><span><strong>刘畅<\/strong>：亲爱的小沙，由于我没能和你共度高三5的生活，目前对你的称呼仍停留在&ldquo;小沙&rdquo;的阶段&hellip;&hellip;不过，神的存在是不需要解释的哈哈哈哈~我最近往往在觉得我自己的苦逼的时候来看看你人人的状态和相册，起到自我激励的效果。。。所以在清华要多注意身体，不然重压之后又会容易生病的= =（当然你进化了就更好~）祝你感冒快点好~学习啊感情啊我就不多说了。。估计别人也说很多了= =过得开心就好~18岁啦~+U哟~<\/span><\/span><\/span><\/p><p>    <strong>火山哥<\/strong>：<span>生日快乐！生活甜美！身体健健康康！ps恭喜沙烨星同学开始成年人的幸福生活！<\/span><\/p><p>    <span><strong>六一姐姐<\/strong>：祝福祝福&hellip;&hellip;撒花撒花&hellip;&hellip;<span>祝沙烨星生日快乐哈~~~PS，施阮同学的画功原来这么好哒~~~<img class=\"mceItem emotion\" src=\"http:\/\/s.xnimg.cn\/\/img\/ems\/good.gif\" border=\"0\" alt=\"赞\"><\/span><\/span><\/p>","title":"给沙神的18岁献礼 之 网络版","view":"525","textlength":"4595","comment":"72","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"22","time":"2012-11-19 23:26:48:000","text":"<p>    <strong>在石头的版本上基本补全了作业，修正了几本书。若有遗漏或差错，记得在原日志回复我~<\/strong><\/p><p>    <strong>普心讨论作业：<\/strong><\/p><p>1．&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 话题：意识<\/p><p>2．&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 记录梦<\/p><p>3．&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 关于进化论的质疑<\/p><p>4．&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 生命存在的意义<\/p><p>5．&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 知识的来源问题（含先天语言获得装置）<\/p><p>6．&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 自由意志与决定论<\/p><p>7．&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 自我被本我完全压抑是否道德<\/p><p>8．&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 阴影<\/p><p>9．&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 怎样看待马斯洛的自我实现<\/p><p>10． 生理基础和意识的关系<\/p><p>11． 大脑边缘系统<\/p><p>12． 感官与现实的关系<\/p><p>13． 设计感觉实验（感觉适应、闪光融合、视觉屏蔽）<\/p><p>14． 潜意识和意识、不同范式下对意识的理解（含一元论心理学）<\/p><p>15． 设计错觉、知觉恒常性、知觉理解性实验<\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <strong>阅读书目：<\/strong><\/p><p>    <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">心理学流派与文明相关<\/span><\/p><p>《心理学思想的流变》<\/p><p>《弗洛伊德与马克思》<\/p><p>《爱欲与文明》<\/p><p>《荣格之道》<\/p><p>《道德的彼岸》-尼采<\/p><p>《论道德的谱系》<\/p><p>《道德经》-陈鼓应<\/p><p>《心经》<\/p><p>《超越自由与尊严》斯金纳<\/p><p>《第二性》波伏娃<\/p><p>杜小真解读萨特《存在与虚无》<\/p><p>拉普拉斯妖（思考决定论）<\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>《鼠疫》《百年孤独》《项狄传》（报告推荐）<\/p><p>《疯子在左，天才在右》（读书推荐）<\/p><p>    <em>Classical philosophy<\/em> Terence Irwin（读书推荐）<\/p><p>《不能承受之重》（读书推荐）<\/p><p>GEB（《哥德尔、埃舍尔、巴赫》）（读书推荐）<\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Positive psychology<\/span><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">相关：<\/span><\/p><p>《西藏生死书》<\/p><p>弗兰克尔<em>Men&rsquo;s search for meaning<\/em><\/p><p>《佛教哲学》<\/p><p>《信念的力量》<\/p><p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <strong>文献：<\/strong><\/p><ol>    <li>On making the right choice: deliberation-without-attention<\/li>    <li>Positive illusion and well-being a social psychological perception on mental health (<em>Psychological Bulletin<\/em>,1988<em>)<\/em>    <\/li>    <li>Sadder but wiser<\/li>    <li>perceptual mechanisms of implicit memory<\/li><\/ol>","title":"普通心理学：作业、书目、文献","view":"140","textlength":"1717","comment":"4","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"0","time":"2012-11-13 14:59:01:000","text":"<p align=\"center\">What do you think?<\/p><p align=\"center\">Poll results vary widely depending on how the question is framed.<\/p><p>    <span>Nov 1, 2011<\/span><\/p><p>From <em>Prospect <\/em>p19-20<\/p><p>(因为版权的关系，截取了些有意思的方面。原文可以搜索EBSCO数据库，关键词&ldquo;What do you think\" &amp;\"Peter Kellner&rdquo;)<\/p><p>民意调查的结果受问卷措辞和上下文的影响。<\/p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 为了避免含沙射影的问题造成的偏差&mdash;&mdash;诸如Do you think Britain should allow the tinpot dictators in Brussels to tell us what to do? 于是他们选择的话题是BBC的license fee【相当于我们的有线电视费】。他们用不同提问的模式询问了2000多人。<\/p><p>（1）最简单的问法<\/p><p>只问问题：总的来说，你认为BBC的license fee值不值这钱？结果回答值和不值的各占一半。【这能做到正好对半开，实验员的运气实在不错&hellip;&hellip;】<\/p><p>（2） 第二种问法<\/p><p>除了问题外，只告诉路人甲license fee要145.5英镑一年。随后，81人中，27人选择值，54人选择不值。比例1:2.<\/p><p>（3）第三种问法<\/p><p>除了问题外，只告诉路人乙license fee要40便士一天。（选值的人数）-（选不值的人数）=+8【40便士怎么来的？145.5&divide;365&asymp;0.4英镑】<\/p><p>（4）第四种问法<\/p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 除了问题外，只告诉路人丙Sky公司有个package，每月19.5英镑，而BBC的license fee要12.13英镑。偏向Sky的人要比BBC的多。但当实验员又很邪恶地告诉路人丁们，Sky的高级套装（包括体育和电影频道）要55.75英镑一个月，选BBC的人又比选Sky的人多了。<\/p><p>（5）第五种问法<\/p><p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 让路人戊们先回答热身问题：觉得BBC的服务怎么样啊？结果四分之三的人认为满意。【天文数字&hellip;&hellip;】然后实验员又很邪恶地告诉他们，一天要40便士噢，还是有+25个人选择值这个价。<\/p><p>    <img thumbnail=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn063\/20121113\/1405\/large_Iyab_5cb10000dfe7118f.jpg\" title=\"photo-media\" src=\"http:\/\/fmn.rrimg.com\/fmn063\/20121113\/1405\/large_Iyab_5cb10000dfe7118f.jpg\" border=\"0\"><\/p><p>文章最有意思的地方在于：当设计问卷的时候，实验者应该告知路人们多少信息？尤其是在询问观点、态度等相对抽象的问题上。若实验员没有界定清楚的话，得到的答案或许是脱离现实却貌似可信的。就像是用一个理想化的模型回答现实的问题。假设是理想化的，得到的结论还是理想化的。那大概不能算实证吧<span>= =<\/span>。。（鉴于最近大家似乎都很喜欢发问卷<span>&hellip;&hellip;<\/span>）<\/p>","title":"What do you think? Poll results vary widely depending on how the question is framed","view":"46","textlength":"1671","comment":"9","access":"0","type":"0"}
{"share":"1","time":"2012-11-05 12:49:07:000","text":"<p>&nbsp;<\/p><p>    <p>        <h1>            <span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt;\"><a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/17Mcpl\">http:\/\/www.guardian.co.uk\/world\/2012\/sep\/30\/kofi-annan-dont-pick-fight<\/a><\/span>        <\/h1>        <h1>Kofi Annan: 'Sometimes you don't have to pick a fight to get your way'<\/h1>        <ul>            <li>                <img title=\"Contributor picture\" class=\"contributor-pic-small\" src=\"http:\/\/static.guim.co.uk\/sys-images\/Guardian\/Pix\/pictures\/2010\/8\/3\/1280824719378\/decca.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"decca\" width=\"60\" height=\"60\"><span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\">Decca Aitkenhead<\/span>            <\/li>            <li>                <span style=\"font-size: 10.0pt;\"><a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/q0FDtm\">The Guardian<\/a>,&nbsp;Sunday 30 September 2012 20.00 BST<\/span>            <\/li>        <\/ul>    <\/p><\/p><p>    <p>        <p>            <img src=\"http:\/\/static.guim.co.uk\/sys-images\/Guardian\/Pix\/pictures\/2012\/9\/28\/1348846091413\/Kofi-Annan-010.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Kofi Annan\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\"><p>Kofi Annan: 'The &shy;national interest still often trumps the broader interest.' Photograph: David Levene for the Guardian<\/p>        <\/p>        <p>            <p>When you have been secretary general of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/diJUuR\">United Nations<\/a>&nbsp;for 10 years, it's never going to be easy to slip into humdrum anonymity.&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/23FPf4\">Kofi Annan<\/a>&nbsp;gave it a good go. On leaving office he and his wife borrowed a friend's Italian hideaway, deep in the forests near Lake Como, and retreated into eight weeks of blissful solitude. With no TV, no radio, no papers; Annan was free, finally, from the clamour of the world's troubles. Two weeks in, he began to get bored.<\/p>            <p>\"Let's go to the tobacconist in the village,\" he suggested, \"and buy a paper.\"<\/p>            <p>They had been in the shop for less than five minutes before his heart sank. A group of men were gathered in the corner, staring. \"Oh no!\" he whispered to his wife. \"We've got six weeks to go, and we've blown our cover. How are we going to manage?\" One of the men approached and thrust out a pen and paper. \"Morgan Freeman, may I have an autograph?\" Annan flashed his best Hollywood smile, scribbled \"Morgan Freeman\" and fled.<\/p>            <p>\"So when people say: 'Here's a man who needs no introduction,'\" he chuckles. \"I say to them, careful!\"<\/p>            <p>As he's telling the story it occurs to me that a tourist's failure to recognise his successor would not constitute an amusing anecdote. Annan does have a curiously movie-star presence, flawlessly crisp and unusually still, but five years after leaving office he remains a more commanding presence in world affairs than&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/hlUR8N\">Ban Ki Moon<\/a>. \"I thought retirement was going to be easier,\" he smiles, \"but I discover it's hard work. I should do what Mandela says and retire from retirement one day.\"<\/p>            <p>We meet just a few weeks after he stood down as the&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/sMxHbP\">UN's special envoy to Syria<\/a>, and his dismay at the ongoing carnage clearly hasn't faded. It's equally clear, however, that he saw no choice but to quit. \"The first thing I said to the security council was: 'This is a near-impossible task. I'm going to try, but I can only do it if I have your united and sustained support.' Because you need that support in order to put pressure on all the parties. 'United' is key. Be united.\" But the security council remained divided, and as a consequence, Annan says gravely: \"The Syrians are going to pay the price. It's an innocent people caught in the middle.\"<\/p>            <p>The plight of&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/1CoKqy\">Syria<\/a>&nbsp;is, in a sense, an extension of Annan's new book, or an illustration of its fundamental message.&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/k0ZSsB\">Interventions: A Life In War and Peace<\/a>&nbsp;tells the story of his 50-year UN career, and of the emerging role of UN peacekeeping. It's a role with which Annan has been intimately linked, but humanitarian intervention &ndash; like Syria's future today &ndash; lies ultimately at the whim of the security council.<\/p>            <p>                <img src=\"http:\/\/cdn.theguardian.tv\/brightcove\/poster\/2012\/8\/2\/120802AnnanStatement_6497338.jpg\" border=\"0\"><\/p>            <span><span>Kofi Annan quits as international envoy to Syria.&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/hRNwj6\">Link to this video<\/a><\/span><\/span>            <p>Until the early 90s, UN peacekeeping efforts had been minimal, most conflicts being adjudicated by the world's two superpowers, whose hostility ensured a security council too divided to authorise more than a handful of peacekeeping missions. Between 1987 and 1992 barely a single UN mission consisted of more than 100 observers, facing little personal risk. By 1994, however, 80,000 UN troops were deployed in highly dangerous warzones. Annan took charge of peacekeeping in 1993, and his book provides a fascinating account of the new challenges facing a security council that, no longer paralysed by division, finds itself the repository of global demands for something to be done about pretty much every problem in the world.<\/p>            <p>\"Time and again, when member states and the governments are faced with an insoluble problem, and they're under pressure to do something, that something usually ends up being referred to the UN.\" He allows a wry chuckle. \"The security council is dealing it with it, so they can relax. And you get the mandates, yes. You just don't get the commensurate resources to deal with it, so you are bound to run into difficulties and fail. And then be blamed. One of my predecessors used to say the letters SG [secretary general] stood for scapegoat.\"<\/p>            <p>The new appetite for humanitarian intervention was in its honeymoon period in 1993, when UN forces were committed in Somalia to what then US secretary of state Madeleine Albright declared \"an unprecedented enterprise aimed at nothing less than the restoration of an entire country\". But after rebels downed two US helicopters, the Americans pulled out, and the UN mission collapsed. The legacy of this failure, Annan writes, explains why the UN stood by and watched a massacre unfold in Rwanda a year later. When the world belatedly woke up to the genocide, UN peacekeepers were blamed for member states' reluctance to risk their own troops' lives.<\/p>            <p>When it came to Kosovo in 1999, Russian support for Serbia ruled out any chance of a security council resolution mandating troops. For the first time in the history of the UN, its secretary general endorsed military action conducted by Nato without the authorisation of the security council. It was, by Annan's account, the ultimate moral dilemma; do loyalties lie with the UN and the rule of law, or with innocent civilians being slaughtered? He stands by his support for the Nato airstrikes, but warned at the time that unless the security council was restored as the sole source of legitimacy, the world would be \"on a dangerous path to anarchy\". That prediction proved horribly prescient four years later, when the security council failed to pass a second resolution authorising an invasion of&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/tR4ra5\">Iraq<\/a>, and the war went ahead anyway. The war came close to costing him his job &ndash; but to many of his admirers it became his finest moment.<\/p>            <p>Annan was always doubtful about the extent of Saddam's hidden WMDs. \"The UN inspectors had been in there for quite a long time, and destroyed quite a few arms; in fact, people argued that they destroyed more weapons than the first gulf war. So the feeling was that he may have had something, but how massive, and the nature of the weapons, was unsure.\" So why wouldn't Saddam co-operate with the inspections? \"He had been bluffing to his neighbours for so many years, telling them: 'I'm powerful, I've got these weapons, don't mess with me.' It was a psychological bluff. So he couldn't bear to admit that actually he'd lied. I think that was the explanation.\"<\/p>            <p>Annan's great regret was to appoint a gung-ho weapons inspector, insensitive to the delicacy of Iraqi military pride. Richard Butler, he writes, was \"a colossal mistake and one of the worst appointments I ever made\". Why? \"In a place like Baghdad, where the people are very nationalistic, you need to find a way to work with them. You cannot go there and throw your weight around.\"<\/p>            <p>He still winces at the memory of all the grandstanding that led inexorably to war. Bizarrely, in the midst of all&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/ckMa1D\">George Bush<\/a>'s fighting talk, the president told Annan: \"It brings tears to my eyes to think of what the Iraqi people are going through under Saddam.\" Annan is generous enough to say: \"I think it was genuine; I don't think it would be crocodile tears,\" but pretty blunt about Bush's other motives. \"There was quite a bit of that in the air, that he was trying to finish his dad's job. And the advisers around him also wanted that. They were also thinking, we kill two birds with one stone &ndash; we get rid of a bad dictator, and get rid of the weapons.\" What about the third bird &ndash; Iraq's oil reserves? \"Well that's what people say,\" Annan agrees with a chuckle. Those who say it have often been dismissed as lefty conspiracy theorists &ndash; but when I ask if Annan would say it himself, he replies without hesitation: \"Yes. It was a country with resources in a region of extreme importance to the world. I'm not sure if Iraq had been as poor as Somalia that there would have been that interest in going to save the country.\"<\/p>            <span><img src=\"http:\/\/static.guim.co.uk\/sys-images\/Guardian\/Pix\/pictures\/2012\/9\/28\/1348846778904\/Kofi-Annan-in-Naqura-Leba-010.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Kofi Annan in Naqura, Lebanon\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\"><span>Kofi Annan in Naqura, Lebanon in 2006, flanked by UN peacekeeping troops Photograph: Zohra Bensemra\/AP<\/span><\/span>            <p>He is less sure about&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/vAdybB\">Tony Blair<\/a>'s motivation. \"Tony, at his best, in his heyday, would have been one of the most brilliant politicians of his time. But how he got himself entangled with this &hellip; I think there was a genuine friendship with Bush, but perhaps there was greater need on Tony's side than on Bush's. I wasn't sure if Tony genuinely wanted to go to war, or was just trying to protect the special relationship, and the special relationship trumped everything. It's difficult to say, because at the beginning he appeared to be on the right side, and he was also in favour of a second resolution. I hoped that would have been the point where you tell George: 'George, you are on your own. I'm not following you on this without the council resolution.' And I wonder what George would have said.\" Does he think it might have stopped him? \"I think it could have made a big difference.\"<\/p>            <p>In 2007, Blair was appointed special envoy to the Quartet, a diplomatic mission created in 2002 by Annan himself to represent the US, EU, UK and Russia in peace talks on Palestine. I found Blair's appointment baffling, and tell Annan I struggle to see how he could &hellip; \"Do it?\" Annan completes the sentence. \"Yeah, yeah.\" So he shares the bewilderment? \"I share some of that. I was surprised that he accepted the role. And nothing much is happening on that dossier. For the past four to five years there has been no real Middle East mediation.\"<\/p>            <p>Annan famously declared the Iraq war illegal, and has never regretted it. \"Because that was my genuine belief.\" But the price he paid took even him by surprise; \"The UN got attacked, and I got attacked personally. The Oil For Food situation was used to beat me up and also beat up the UN.\" The US made allegations of widespread corruption under the Oil For Food programme, which Annan believes were motivated entirely by a desire to punish him, for they took a sinister turn when his own son, Kojo, became implicated. Kojo had worked for a Swiss company, which in 1998 won a contract under the programme; he left the company that same year, but then came the revelation that, unbeknown to his father, it had continued to pay him for a further five years. Annan was mortified. \"And furious.\"<\/p>            <p>It must have tested the father-son relationship to breaking point. \"Yes,\" he agrees uneasily, \"A friend of mine said: 'It's tough for you, but I also feel for your son. You come under the microscope not because of something you've done or who you are, but because of your father &ndash; and that makes life difficult for a young person.' But I said: 'There are certain things you just don't do.'\" Why hadn't Kojo told his father about the ongoing payments? \"Maybe, sometimes, if you think you need help from Daddy, you probably don't share all the information. I don't know. We're talking about a boy who was 22, 23 at the time. But now we are OK.\"<\/p>            <p>The pressure from Washington was ferocious, but he never seriously contemplated resignation. \"It may have fleetingly crossed my mind. Sometimes you feel: 'Who needs this? Why should one put up with this?' But I felt it was a witch-hunt. So to walk away and give them the feeling that they have won? No.\"<\/p>            <p>For all its ugliness, the onslaught against Annan was in essence no more than a manifestation of the fundamental tension underscoring his whole diplomatic career &ndash; the conflict between national self-interest, or realpolitik, and the loftier ideal of international law embodied by the organisation Annan served for 50 years.<\/p>            <p>\"They clash, they clash,\" he agrees, with a smile. \"I think we've made progress, but you are right &ndash; the national interest still often trumps the broader interest. But what governments and people don't realise is that sometimes the collective interest &ndash; the international interest &ndash; is also the national interest.\"<\/p>            <p>Born in 1938 into a powerful Ghanaian tribe, Annan had a privileged childhood in what was the Gold Coast, coming of age as his country won independence from Britain. Awarded a scholarship to study in America, he assumed he'd return to serve his nation, but a job with the World Health Organisation in Geneva introduced him to a \"worldly and engaging environment\", which made him reassess his loyalties. \"I began,\" he writes, \"to realise that community for me would mean something different from what it had meant to my father's generation.\"<\/p>            <span><img src=\"http:\/\/static.guim.co.uk\/sys-images\/Guardian\/Pix\/pictures\/2012\/9\/28\/1348846298199\/Kofi-Annanon-Sesame-Stree-010.jpg\" border=\"0\" alt=\"Kofi Annanon Sesame Street\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\"><span>Kofi Annan makes an appearance on Sesame Street in 2001. Photograph: AP<\/span><\/span>            <p>How does someone with so little personal sense of national loyalty get through to men for whom it is everything? I've always wondered what Annan says to world leaders &ndash; often monstrous tyrants, even crypto-terrorists &ndash; to win their trust and persuade them to make peace. The book is full of references to marathon late-night phone calls to warring parties, and the art, he says, is quite simple. You have to understand what drives them, appeal to their pride and vanity, and offer them a way out that saves face.<\/p>            <p>\"Dignity is very important. It's about dignity. Without beating up on them, I say: 'If you're really a leader, and are interested in the interests of your people, you have to lead; you have to show courage. If you are really a strong man as you say you are, you have to look out for the weak in your society. Look at what you're doing to them.' They have to feel that you have their interests at heart. These are people with egos, and a sense of legacy, so you ask: 'What legacy are you going to leave?' Saddam probably saw himself as a modern-day&nbsp;<a href=\"http:\/\/rrurl.cn\/2DF09S\">Saladin<\/a>&nbsp;&ndash; the glorious Arab warrior. He saw himself as someone who was building his nation. So you tell him: 'You want all this destroyed? How do you think you will be judged?'<\/p>            <p>\"That matters, because these people often have a certain image of themselves, and they will go to an incredible extent to protect themselves. So I tell them what their actions mean, how they are seen by the outside world.\"<\/p>            <p>I suspect Annan must struggle to imagine how he will be judged himself, for his identity is so subsumed within that of the UN as to be almost indivisible. When I ask him to name the single greatest misconception about him, his first response is telling. \"About me, or about the UN?\" About him, I say. He falls into lengthy silent thought.<\/p>            <p>\"That he's too soft,\" he offers eventually. \"Because they feel he doesn't pound the table &ndash; not assertive enough. But it doesn't bother me, because sometimes you don't have to fight to get your way. You don't have to pick a fight to get them to change their mind, or get them to see things your way. You really don't.\"<\/p>        <\/p>    <\/p><\/p>","title":"The Guardian\u2014\u2014Kofi Annan: &#39;Sometimes you don&#39;t have to pick a fight to get your way&#39;","view":"49","textlength":"17288","comment":"8","access":"0","type":"0"}
